<FIRST>u a AM-DeltaTurbulence 5thLd-Writethru a0403 06-17 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Delta Turbulence, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0403,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Turbulence Shakes Up Delta Flight; 25 Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `It was...' to UPDATE with FAA comment; SUBS
7th graf, `Delta spokeswoman...' to RESTORE dropped reference to airport;
picks up 8th graf pvs, `The jet...; Should stand for AMs.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX3</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delta Air Lines jet hit turbulence Friday and
those people not wearing seat belts ``were flying through the air,''
a passenger said. Twenty-five people were taken to hospitals,
including one with broken ribs.
   ``The kids were screaming and the food was flying and the people
were flying,'' said Brenda Chevalier of Seattle, who was treated for
a sprained back at South Fulton Hospital.
   ``It's like you're on a roller coaster and at the top of a hill,
the way your stomach feel,'' she said. ``There's no control _ you've
lost it. I thought I was going to die. I kept screaming, `God,
please be with us.'''
   The Federal Aviation Administration said it had no measurement of
how far the jet dropped, but ``It was probably more like a two
second free fall that seemed liked 20 seconds,'' said FAA spokesman
Jack Barker.
   One passenger was in an intensive care unit and four others
remained hospitalized Friday night, said spokeswoman Ann Renner of
South Fulton Hospital, where 12 other passengers were treated and
released.
   A Shallowford Hospital official said one passenger was admitted
in stable condition with a concussion. One passenger was being held
for observation at Georgia Baptist Hospital and one was released.
Five were treated and released at Clayton General Hospital.
   Delta spokeswoman Glenda Hatchett Johnson said several more
passengers were treated for bruises by paramedics at Hartsfield
International Airport in Atlanta.
   The jet, which was traveling from Seattle to Atlanta, entered an
area of unexpected air turbulence while flying about 25,000 feet
over Alabama, said Delta spokesman Jim Lundy. It landed at
Hartsfield at 3:45 p.m.
   Flight 102 carried 282 passengers.
   A passenger who wasn't injured, Linda Alexander from Seattle,
said anybody not wearing their seat belt was in danger.
   ``As it (the plane) dropped, anyone not fastened in went up and a
lot of people were flying through the air,'' she said.
   Ms. Johnson said the seat-belt light was on at the time.
   John Martin of Chattanooga, Tenn., said flight attendants were
serving passengers when the plane hit the air pocket and, although
they were thrown too, helped injured passengers.
   Delta spokesman Neil Monroe said two flight attendants were
injured but not seriously.
   Ms. Chevalier said the pilot had told passengers at the start of
the trip that it was his last flight after 33 years of flying. When
the plane landed at Hartsfield, the pilot was ``crying like a
baby,'' she said.
   Ms. Johnson said Delta would not release the pilot's name.
   Also Friday, a Northwest Airlines jet en route from Seattle to
Detroit made an unscheduled landing in Bismarck, N.D., after one of
its engines developed an oil leak, authorities said.
   No injuries were reported in that incident.
</TEXT>
