<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary-History     06-17 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary-History,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nagy Case Illustrates Trend to More Accurate History in Soviet Bloc</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Saturday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hungary</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIOREL URMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The reburial of Imre Nagy as a martyr 31
years after his execution as a traitor illustrates the Soviet bloc's
increasing tendency to discard official Stalinist histories and
accept events as they were.
   Encouraged by the Soviet exposure of Josef Stalin's excesses,
Hungary and Poland are confronting long-avoided questions about the
1956 uprising crushed by Soviet tanks in the streets of Budapest and
the murder of Polish officers by the Soviets in the woods of Katyn.
   Rewriting history has been common in the communist world since
the Bolshevik Revolution of 1917.
   ``Rehabilitation'' is the term often used when honor is restored
to former leaders disgraced or executed by ascendant rivals, who
often, in their turn, also fall from power.
   Although the current view of history is far more honest, there
still are elements of tailoring it to political ends.
   In the Soviet Union, Mikhail S. Gorbachev has expressed
disapproval of Leonid I. Brezhnev but to some degree has
rehabilitated Nikita S. Khrushchev, whom Brezhnev discredited.
   Brezhnev now stands for the corrupt, stagnant policies Gorbachev
seeks to change and Khrushchev is seen as the forerunner of the
re-examination of Stalin's dictatorship.
   Nikolai I. Bukharin and other old Bolsheviks purged by Stalin
also have had their respectibility restored.
   Leon Trotsky, who commanded the Red Army in the civil war after
1917 and lost the power struggle to Stalin, has not been
rehabilitated but the Kremlin's view of him seems kinder. Trotsky
was living in Mexico in 1940 when an assassin sent by Stalin killed
him with an ax.
   In the turbulence of the communist world, rehabilitation
sometimes is quick.
   Solidarity was born in Poland in 1980, during a strike led by
Lech Walesa, and outlawed in 1982. Walesa was detained for months
and the independent union was reviled.
   Seven years later, Solidarity negotiated free elections with the
government and the voters gave it a stunning victory.
   When communist demigods die, criticism can grow just as quickly.
   President Tito was unchallenged in Yugoslavia from World War II
until his death in 1980, but his policies are being questioned nine
years later and elaborate birthday festivities have been abandoned.
   Milovan Djilas, once heir apparent but later imprisoned by Tito
for nine years because of his dissident views, has made a comeback
after 36 years of being ostracized.
   ``If Tito's reign had been shorter, there would have been many
fewer doubts cast on his merits,'' Djilas, a successful writer, said
recently.
   Friday's reburial in Hungary represented almost a complete
reversal of political fortunes for Nagy and Janos Kadar, who took
over after the Soviets crushed the 1956 revolt.
   Kadar, initially reviled, gained respect in the 1960s for
releasing many of those jailed in the revolt and for pursuing
political and economic reform.
   He put brakes on reform in the 1970s, however, and when he
resigned last year had become a symbol of economic stagnation and
political rigidity.
   Last month, the Central Commmittee of the Communist Party
criticized Kadar, while hailing Nagy as a symbol of reform.
   This week, the government declared said it ``rejects the
erroneous and indeed reprehensible political decisions of the past,
the reprisals that followed 1956.''
   Czechoslovakia, evidently worried that Nagy's reburial might draw
attention to the case of Alexander Dubcek, said Thursday ``enemies
of socialism'' might abuse the change in official sentiment.
   Dubcek was Communist Party chief in Czechoslovakia during the
``Prague Spring'' of reform that was crushed by a Soviet-led
invasion in August 1968. He now lives in relative obscurity.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890617-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Chad-GabaDeath     06-17 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Chad-Gaba Death,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Confirms Death of AP Employee</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>N'DJAMENA, Chad (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has confirmed the death of
Salet Gaba, an employee of The Associated Press for 20 years, nearly
two years after reporting his detention.
   In an interview Tuesday in the N'Djamena, Information Minister
Adoum Moussa Seif said Gaba was killed by an army patrol in central
Guera province in 1987. The government alleges Gaba was involved in
an armed rebellion.
   Last December, the London-based human rights organization Amnesty
International said Gaba was killed by security forces in a N'Djamena
prison sometime in mid-1988.
   Previously, the official radio and President Hissene Habre had
said Gaba was in prison awaiting trial. On Tuesday, Moussa Seif
denied the Amnesty report but did not explain the contradiction
between previous official statements and his new version of how Gaba
died.
   Amnesty International first reported that Gaba, who dropped out
of sight in December 1986 fearing arrest, was detained on July 14,
1987, in Mongo, capital of his home region of Guera, and was being
held without charge in N'Djamena.
   The official Chad radio, the Central African nation's only
station, reported his detention in August 1987, but said Gaba was
arrested ``neither for his opposition to the regime of President
Hissene Habre, nor for his beliefs and even less for tribal
reasons.''
   It said he was arrested ``after having been caught with weapons
in his hands ... and because he is the author of the deaths of two
peasants.''
   At a news conference during the French-African summit in December
1987, Habre said Gaba was ``captured in a state of rebellion'' and
was to be tried for illegal possession of arms.
   Chad is a sparsely populated former French colony that has been
torn by civil war almost constantly since independence in 1960.
Gaba, a member of the minority Hadjerai ethnic group, worked for
Agence France-Presse, the French news agency, before joining the AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
