<FIRST>u a AM-BankSiege 1stLd-Writethru a0780 06-17 0599</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bank Siege, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0780,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Officer Shot, Suspect Killed in Foiled Bank Job; Two People Sought</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 15th graf, `The driver...' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
identity and charges; picks up 16th graf pvs, `Officers surrounded...</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhotos MH8, MH9</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL WARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HALLANDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bank robbers escaped during a
shootout Friday that left a police officer wounded and an accomplice
dead.
   A fourth man, the getaway driver, was arrested outside City
National Bank of Hallandale after his car was riddled by police
bullets. One of the fugitives may also have been wounded, police
said.
   Police did not realize the men had escaped until a siege of
several hours ended when a SWAT team dropped in from a helicopter
and did not find anyone inside.
   The robbers used a guard's uniform to fool employees as they
arrived at the bank in the morning. They also seemed familiar with
the bank's operation, police said.
   ``It was well planned,'' Police Chief Richard Fox said. ``It
takes some planning if this person had a security guard's uniform
on. They apparently knew the routine. It was not sloppy at all.''
   Hallandale police Lt. David Miles, 42, a 16-year veteran, was in
stable condition at Hollywood Memorial Hospital with gunshot wounds
to the cheek and the groin, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Miles' new bulletproof vest, which stopped the shot aimed at his
groin, probably saved his life, said police Sgt. Jack Kudrick.
   ``We understand he just started wearing one a week ago,'' said
City Manager R.J. Intindola. ``He's lucky he did because he was shot
at point-blank range.''
   The robbery attempt began just before 7 a.m., FBI spokesman Paul
Miller said when the phony guard let bank employees in and then tied
them up.
   A silent alarm was sounded as the robbers tried to force an
employee to open the vault. The bank's vault was never opened,
authorities said.
   As Hallandale officer Daniel O'Connell, 44, responded to the
alarm, he was disarmed and tied up.
   That officer was followed by Miles, who exchanged shots with the
suspects.
   ``The officer who had been held hostage broke away and as he went
out of the bank, exchanged shots,'' Miller said. Four bank employees
were able to walk out as they saw police arrive.
   One robber, identified only as a Nicaraguan, was felled in a hail
of bullets as he fled the bank, dying several feet from the getaway
car.
   The driver emerged unscathed even though the car windows were
shot out, and he was taken into custody. Pedro A. Sonarrida of
Hialeah was charged with first-degree murder, attempted homicide,
armed robbery and false imprisonment.
   The murder charge stems from the death of his cohort during the
commission of a felony.
   Officers surrounded the bank for what they assumed was a standoff
with robbers inside. Shortly before 11 a.m., a helicopter dropped
six SWAT team members onto the bank's roof, but a search of the
building turned up no suspects.
   One witness said she saw one man jump on a bus when the shooting
first broke out.
   ``I saw three guys running this way. One got killed. One ran into
a bus, and the other I don't know where he went,'' said Carmen
Melgar, 50, a hair stylist across the street who said she was nearly
shot herself when a bullet shattered her window.
   ``I feel so lucky ... like I'm born again,'' she said.
   The bank's regular security guard is missing, and police aren't
sure if he is in trouble relating to the foiled bank robbery.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
