<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0333EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-US-China Bjt   06-17 0570</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-China, Bjt,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Offering Shelter to More Chinese Diplomats</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's decision to offer protection
to all Chinese citizens in the United States has paved the way for
at least two more Chinese diplomats to obtain refuge here.
   A State Department official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said Friday that besides the two Chinese diplomats who announced in
San Francisco they intended to defect, ``there have been additional
Chinese officials who have asked for protection in the United
States.''
   He refused to give a specific number who have sought refuge, nor
to confirm a report that a husband and wife, both diplomats in the
Chinese Embassy in Washington, were the diplomats in question.
   According to published and broadcast reports, those two are Han
Guohong, secretary to the ambassador, and her husband Zhang Chiwei,
an attache in the press office at the embassy in Washington. There
was no one available for comment at the embassy early today.
   The move to offer the additional Chinese diplomats refuge came as
more people were arrested in China for taking part in pro-democracy
protests and China's leaders increased efforts to absolve the
government of the bloody attack on protesters in Tiananmen Square.
   The official said the Chinese diplomats who have asked for
protection have not formally asked for asylum, but could do so in
the future.
   He explained that the diplomats are covered under Bush's decision
to grant all Chinese citizens in the United States permission to
remain here until June 1990.
   On Monday, Zhou Li-min, 26, a Chinese vice consul in San
Francisco for cultural affairs, and Zhang Li-min, 25, vice consul
for overseas affairs, announced plans to defect. Immigration
officials said the two were in hiding after meeting with FBI and
immigration authorities.
   There are believed to be some 73,000 Chinese students in the
United States, as well as some 250,000 visitors and business people
who could be eligible under Bush's offer.
   Chinese diplomats based in Canada, Australia and Japan are also
reported to have sought refuge in those countries.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Bush deplores
the persecutions of Chinese who demonstrated for democracy but has
no current plans to impose further sanctions or interruption of
relations with China.
   ``We continue to watch the situation,'' said Fitzwater. ``We'll
continue to measure it as we go forward. Sanctions are always a part
of that review, but we have nothing to announce.''
   Bush has refused to affix blame for China's bloodshed but has
said it would be ``extraordinarily difficult'' for the United States
to have normal relations with officials responsible for the massacre
of students and workers participating in pro-democracy protests.
   U.S. officials repeatedly have stressed the importance of the
relationship between the two countries and Washington's interest in
retaining formal ties.
   Fitzwater declined to characterize Bush's reaction to attempts by
Beijing officials to rewrite the story of the bloody massacre two
weeks ago in Beijing's Tiananmen Square and claim that no
demonstrators were killed.
   But he said anyone who has seen the television reports knows what
happened, despite the Chinese propaganda attempts.
   ``Those matters all speak for themselves ... The pictures and the
reality of the reporting has been so dramatic that these kind of
efforts stand beside them so starkly that I wouldn't even want to
try to diminish that by giving it words,'' Fitzwater said.
</TEXT>
