<FIRST>r w PM-HUDProbe     06-17 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD Probe,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>HUD Inspector Says He Tried to Implement Safeguards</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Aociated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development's chief watchdog says the agency ignored his
recommendations for safeguards against the theft of money from the
sale of foreclosed property with government-insured mortgages.
   Testifying Friday before a House subcommittee, Inspector General
Paul Adams also said the accounts of at least a dozen private agents
in HUD's property sales program nationwide were being examined for
possible misappropriation, fraud and embezzlement.
   One of the agents, nicknamed ``Robin HUD'' because she said she
gave most of her proceeds to the poor, tearfully admitted in
Friday's hearing that she stole $5 million in funds due the
government.
   Quoting Scripture and claiming she ``followed a higher law,''
Mary Louise Harrell told the House subcommittee on housing and
employment, ``I have come forward, as one who loves the Lord, in an
attempt to confess to the world that I diverted government funds.''
   Adams told the subcommittee he had repeatedly warned top agency
officials, including former HUD Secretary Samuel Pierce, that the
system for monitoring money from property sales was weak.
Investigators are trying to track down $20 million from those sales.
   ``HUD has not established effective monitoring systems to assure
that closing agents properly carry out their responsibilities,''
Adams said.
   ``Moreover, planned changes to its automated systems have been
slow, and current systems do not contain all information field
offices need to properly monitor agent activities,'' he added.
   But the inspector general came under fire from lawmakers for
doing nothing when his warnings and recommendations were ignored.
   ``It looks to me like you just covered your rear end because you
told them,'' said Rep. Christopher Shays, R-Conn.
   ``It's your job to make sure this doesn't happen,'' he said.
   Meanwhile, the Wall Street Journal said top officials in the
Reagan administration's Department of Housing and Urban Development
overruled staff objections and awarded a $268,000 grant to a company
run by Republican fundraiser Frederick Bush.
   Bush &amp; Co. subcontracted the technical work for the project, an
economic development plan for Puerto Rico, to another firm for
$125,000 and took the rest of the grant, according to HUD records
obtained by the newspaper.
   Bush was deputy finance chairman for then-Vice President George
Bush's presidential campaign last year and is now the nominee for
ambassador to Luxembourg. He is no relation to President Bush.
   A HUD official said Friday the details of the Journal story were
``absolutely correct.''
</TEXT>
