<FIRST>u i BC-FriendshipFlight     06-17 0381</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Friendship Flight,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>11-Year-Old Pilot in Iceland on Round-the-World Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ASGEIR SVERRISSON</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>REYKJAVIK, Iceland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weary Tony Aliengena, the boy pilot
from Southern California who is attempting to become the youngest
person to fly around the world, landed his small Centurion airplane
in Iceland early Saturday.
   ``I'm tired and I'm really glad to be here as this is one of the
longest legs of the trip,'' the 11-year-old aviator said at
Reykjavik airport.
   He said the five-hour flight from Sondrestrom, Greenland, was
especially difficult because the plane had to buck strong easterly
winds.
   Tony landed his single-engine Cessna 210 turboprop at 2:20 a.m.
(10:20 p.m. EDT Friday) after the journey across the Denmark Strait,
one of the most dangerous stages of his planned epic.
   He said he was ready for a day of rest before heading eastward.
   ``Today we are going to relax and go fishing,'' the boy said.
   ``I second that,'' said his father, Gary Aliengena, who sits
beside him on the flight.
   Everyone involved seemed to be hungry.
   The pilot of a second plane accompanying Tony, with the boy's
mother Susan, 10-year-old sister Alaina and a party of journalists,
was eating what he described as a two-day-old pizza.
   Alaina got out some bread and peanut butter and made herself a
sandwich as she waited for her brother to arrive.
   The third aircraft in the party, carrying a film crew, had to
turn back to Greenland because of a problem with the plane's
gyroscope, the group said.
   Tony said he would not be collecting any local signatures to add
to the 800-foot scroll of signatures he is carrying for presentation
to Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev later this month.
   The scroll bears the signatures of an estimated 200,000 U.S.
schoolchildren and Tony also has letters from the American
youngsters to children in the Soviet Union.
   Tony's father, a real estate investor and devoted pilot who
taught his son to fly while Tony sat on his lap, said they probably
will resume their flight on Sunday morning, heading for Oslo,
Norway. From there they fly to Sweden, the Soviet Union and onward
to Alaska and home.
   Tony set out June 5 from John Wayne Airport at Costa Mesa,
Calif., for the 19,000-mile ``goodwill flight'' dubbed Friendship
Flight '89.
</TEXT>
