<FIRST>r w PM-POWSighting     06-17 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-POW Sighting,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen Ask Bush, Baker For POW Investigation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANE E. ALLEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 40 congressmen are asking the Bush
administration to investigate a Japanese monk's claims that he
shared a prison cell with three captive American soldiers and had
seen as many as 10 American prisoners while in Vietnam.
   In a letter sent Friday to President Bush and Secretary of State
James A. Baker III, the congressmen urged ``a thorough investigation
of this recent account of American POWs in Vietnam.''
   Iwanobu Yoshida, a 65-year-old Buddhist monk imprisoned for 14
years before his release in January, is being treated in a Sapporo
hospital on the island of Hokkaido for physical and mental disorders
stemming from his imprisonment. His daughter, Keiko Takatsuka, has
been interpreting for him because he suffers from a speech
impediment.
   ``Every resource available should be used to determine the fate
of our POWs and MIAs in Vietnam,'' the letter from the congressmen
said. ``We ask you to do all that you can to bring an end to this
uncertainty.''
   Rep. James Saxton, R-N.J., said: ``We have been informed that a
U.S. military attache interviewed the monk a few days ago,''
``However, the administration has elected not to disclose any
information from the meeting at this time.''
   Lisa Zywokarte, a Saxton aide, said officials with the State
Department confirmed that the United States plans to send another
military attache to meet with Yoshida. The first meeting was Monday.
   Yoshida said he recalled seeing ``young and healthy'' Americans
in the prison, but could not remember their names.
   The Vietnamese Embassy in Tokyo has denied Yoshinda's claims,
saying Hanoi holds no prisoners from the war that ended in 1975.
   However, the U.S. government has been pressing for information on
the 2,364 Americans listed as missing in action.
   Yoshida became a monk in 1966, leaving his family behind when he
emigrated to Vietnam to set up a temple in Saigon. He became a South
Vietnamese citizen in 1973 and was arrested in 1975 after North
Vietnamese forces took control of South Vietnam. International human
rights groups secured his release on Jan. 20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
