<DOCNO> AP890617-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0551EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CheapWine Bjt   06-17 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cheap Wine, Bjt,0668</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Makers of Cheap Wine Pulls Brands from Seedy Neighborhood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELISABETH DUNHAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second maker of inexpensive, high-alcohol
wines is pulling the product from stores shelves in the city's seedy
Tenderloin district, although some people doubt the move will curb
alcoholism.
   The manufacturer of Richard's Wild Irish Rose on Friday announced
it was joining E.&amp;J. Gallo in removing cheap wine from the
neighborhood's stores. Gallo said Wednesday it would stop selling
such brands as Thunderbird and Night Train Express to retailers in
the Tenderloin _ San Francisco's Skid Row _ for six months.
   The action came after area distributer Gallo-Bay Cities, owned by
Gallo, met with a group dubbed Safe and Sober Streets that has asked
grocers to stop selling such wines in the neighborhood.
   The group says it is tired of tripping over wine bottles and
being menaced by drunks.
   Thunderbird, Night Train Express and Richard's Wild Irish Rose
are three of the best-selling brands of fortified wines, which are
18 percent alcohol. Regular wine is about 12 percent.
   On Friday, the Canandaigua Wine Co., maker of Richard's Wild
Irish Rose, said the company would no longer sell that brand in the
Tenderloin.
   ``Given our company's position and the specifics of this
situation, we will participate in this program and discontinue
distribution in this area,'' the Canandaigua, N.Y.-based company
said.
   The statement, read by a secretary who would not give her name,
did not say how long the program would last.
   The high-alcohol wines are typically made from the cheapest
ingredients, then mixed with grape brandy to increase the alcoholic
content. They sell for about 90 cents to $1.25 a bottle, typically a
fifth of a gallon.
   ``After I got the news from Gallo, I ordered 250 cases of Wild
Irish Rose,'' Hatim Nassar, owner of Empire Liquor and Grocery, said
Friday.
   Nassar said he is worried that the Gallo pullout will last longer
than six months. He said he has stocked up on a six-month supply of
the Gallo brands and raised the price of each bottle 25 cents.
   ``This is my bread and butter,'' said Nassar, who estimated he
sells about 200 bottles of the cheap wines each day. ``If I don't
continue to sell this, I will have to close my doors and go home.''
   Liquor store owner Peter Wong said he isn't concerned. ``Some
were sorry to see it go, but there's other comparable brands''
people can buy, he said.
   Some of the Tenderloin's hard-drinking crowd hangs out at
Boedeker Park, where the homeless sleep on the lawn and the smell of
urine permeates the air.
   They said the disappearance of the cheap wines won't reduce
alcoholism in the area.
   ``They gonna chip in their money and buy a big expensive
bottle,'' said one man who refused to give his name. ``You ain't
gonna stop a drinking man from drinking. If they don't drink in the
morning, they gonna have a seizure.''
   Allen Keys, 37, who said he goes to the park twice a week to play
ball and hang around, maintained that the district's denizens simply
will walk to another neighborhood, go to another store and bring
cheap wine back.
   Modesto-based Gallo has said if the experiment succeeds in
reducing alcoholism in the Tenderloin, the company will pull those
wines in other neighborhoods.
   Police Officer Bob Geary, who patrols the park, said the
manufacturers' decision against selling to neighborhood retailers is
a ``stopgap measure and an oversimplification of the problem.''
   He said he issues about 11 alcohol-related citations in the park
each day.
   ``I understand what the community is trying to do, but I still
feel that everyone in the free enterprise system has the right to
sell legal goods,'' he said. ``It would be more effective to have
closer policing of the selling of goods to intoxicants and
youngsters.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
