<FIRST>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     06-17 0796</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Washington In Brief,810</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Committee Schedules Lucas Confirmation Hearing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate Judiciary Committee has scheduled a
July 19 confirmation hearing for William Lucas, nominated by
President Bush to be the Justice Department's civil rights chief.
   The hearing will be chaired by Sen. Paul Simon, D-Ill., chairman
of the panel's civil rights subcommittee, Jane Berman, committee
spokeswoman, said Friday.
   The nomination is opposed by several civil rights groups that
contend Lucas, a black Republican, lacks the legal and professional
experience to be assistant attorney general for civil rights.
   Lucas, formerly sheriff and later chief executive of Wayne
County, Mich., said on a committee questionnaire that he has never
tried a case in court since he became a private attorney two years
ago.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Union Cannot Buy Subsidized Soybean Oil</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union will not be able to buy U.S.
soybean oil at subsidized prices, at least not at this time, the
Agriculture Department says.
   Department officials had been under pressure for some time to
sell Moscow vegetable oil under the Export Enhancement Program, or
EEP, which provides subsidies to exporters who then can sell
commodities at reduced prices to designated overseas buyers.
   A one-paragraph statement issued Friday by the department said:
   ``After careful review based upon the criteria and objectives of
the Export Enhancement Program as well as other proposals, the
(department) will not offer a subsidized (EEP) sale of vegetable oil
to the Soviet Union at this time.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>California Is Top Farm Export State Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California was the top farm export state in
1988 for the fourth consecutive year, the Agriculture Department
said.
   Estimates by the department's Economic Research Service had put
California at the top of the U.S. farm export heap for the first
time in 1985. Until then, since the rankings began in the 1960s,
Iowa or Illinois had led.
   ``Fruits, nuts and vegetables accounted for 65 percent of
California's exports,'' the report released Friday said.
``California was the largest supplier of these crops and of seeds.
Total exports of $3.39 billion were the highest for a single state
since Iowa's $3.41 billion in 1982.''
   Only the top 10 states were reported. Those were said to account
for 59 percent of total U.S. exports, which were valued at $35.3
billion in the fiscal year that ended last Sept. 30.
   Iowa replaced Illinois for the No. 2 spot for 1988 export value,
the report showed. Illinois dropped to third. Kansas was fourth,
replacing Nebraska, while Texas was fifth and Nebraska sixth.
Minnesota was ranked seventh; Indiana, eighth; Ohio, ninth; and
Missouri, 10th.
   In fiscal 1987, the rankings were: California, Illinois, Iowa,
Nebraska, Kansas, Texas, Minnesota, Indiana, North Dakota and Ohio.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>American Legion Gets $548,000 Grant from Agent Orange Fund</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Legion said it has received a
$548,000 grant from the Agent Orange fund to develop programs for
helping families of Vietnam veterans, especially those with
developmentally disabled children.
   The money also will be used for programs of counseling and
support for families of Vietnam veterans suffering from
post-traumatic stress disorder and problems with substance abuse.
   Pilot programs will be established in the first year in Kansas,
Kentucky, New York and Pennsylvania where, the Legion said, it
estimates there are 93,000 ``at risk'' veterans. Plans are to
replicate the referral networks throughout the country eventually.
   The grant is from the Agent Orange Class Assistance Program,
established by a federal court in New York, to distribute $52
million over a period of seven to 10 years to meet the needs of
Vietnam veterans and their families.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>---</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department Objects To 48 Georgia Judgeships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Justice Department has objected to Georgia
laws that had created two judicial circuits and 48 elected Superior
Court judgeships over the past 24 years.
   The action was disclosed in a letter to state officials from
James P. Turner, an acting assistant attorney general in the civil
rights division. Under the 1965 Civil Rights Act, the objection
renders the laws legally unenforceable until the department's
objection is withdrawn or overturned in court.
   But Deborah Burstion-Wade, a spokeswoman for the civil rights
division, said Friday the department's objection does not prevent
the 48 sitting judges from continuing to fulfill their duties, nor
does it provide a basis for challenging their past decisions.
   The Voting Rights Act requires that Georgia and other Southern
states submit all voting or election changes to the Justice
Department, which must determine that the changes have neither a
racially discriminatory purpose nor effect before they can take
effect.
   The 48 judgeships covered by the department's objection Friday _
out of 137 total Superior Court judgeships in the state _ all were
created since passage of the Voting Rights Act.
</TEXT>
