<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     06-17 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0489</SECOND>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HACKETTSTOWN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After each had experienced two failed
marriages, Ella Crane and Christopher Nelson decided to make their
wedding a Whopper.
   They were married at a Burger King in a ceremony during which the
bride shoved a Whopper hamburger in the groom's mouth instead of
wedding cake.
   Nelson first set eyes on Ms. Crane about a year ago at the
fast-food eatery, where she is manager.
   ``This is her second home. If anyone would get married here,
Ella's definitely the one to do it,'' said Peggy Volpe, an assistant
manager.
   Mayor Patricia Harper said she used the ``standard verbiage''
uniting Ms. Crane and Nelson, both 34, on Thursday afternoon.
   ``My crew is my family, too, and I wanted them there,'' said Ms.
Crane, who has worked at the restaurant since 1977.
   More than 100 people crowded into the Burger King, including old
customers, people coming in for a quick meal, the regional manager
and employees, Ms. Volpe said.
   The bride arrived in a limousine, and a tape of ``Here Comes The
Bride'' began as she walked down the aisle past the soda machine.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman gave birth to a boy on a stalled subway
train, and the Transit Authority foreman who helped suggested that
she ``name the kid `C Train''' after the vehicle in which he was
born.
   But she quickly thought better of it and named the boy after him.
   ``There's so many negative things happening on the trains these
days. And a perfect stranger. He was a really nice guy,'','' the
32-year-old mother, Kathy Quiles, said from her hospital bed.
   Mother and child _ 7-pound, 2-ounce Joseph Ramiro Casiano _ were
in good condition. A hospital spokeswoman said the child was in
isolation only because he was born outside of the hospital and had
initial difficulties.
   Ms. Quiles said she was hurrying home after a clinic visit Friday
because she thought she was going to go into labor. She was with her
husband, Ramiro Casiano, who had assisted in the births of their six
other children.
   The brakes on the train on which they were riding malfunctioned,
and maintenance supervisor Joseph Caracciolo was trying to check on
his men working down the line, when he asked a conductor what was
going on.
   It was apparent the pregnant woman was going to give birth.
Caracciolo, two teen-age girls and a woman assisted.
   Once the baby was born, Caracciolo demanded that the train get
moving and told the conductor to have an ambulance standing by.
   ``Everybody worked great,'' Caracciolo said. ``All the people
were cheering from the other cars. Everybody was hugging and
cheering and carrying on.
   ``There were no bad guys. For 15 minutes there was no hatred in
the world. It was a nice feeling.''
</TEXT>
