<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0420EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon-Christians Bjt   06-17 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Christians, Bjt,0805</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weeks of Syrian Shelling Leaves Christian Enclave a Ghost Town</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOUNIEH, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 12 weeks of shelling by Syrian
forces, this once-bustling Christian enclave north of Beirut has
become a ghost town.
   The daily artillery fire, which drove most of its 1 million
residents into underground bunkers and shelters, has sapped the life
from an area once called the Monte Carlo of the Middle East.
   Although the intensity of shellfire has eased since the Arab
League called for a cease-fire May 11, the Christians _ outnumbered
and outgunned by Syria and its allies _ have been paralyzed by an
acute gasoline shortage.
   ``If it's not shelling, it's gas and if it's not gas it's
something else,'' said Samira Khater, a secretary.
   There is hardly any traffic on the roads. Few people are able to
drive to work.
   Half the shops, hidden behind sandbags and earth-filled oildrums,
are shuttered.
   Factories that survived the ferocious shelling limp along with
skeleton staffs and whatever fuel they can scrounge.
   Restaurants are lucky if they get 10 customers a day.
   And the night life that once throbbed in the clubs, bars and
restaurants along the Mediterranean coastline is dead.
   Closed is the famous Casino du Liban overlooking Jounieh Bay, 12
miles north of Beirut, where oil-rich sheiks from the Persian Gulf
and high-rollers from around the world once gambled.
   It was a regular target for the Syrian gunners who have battled
the forces of Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun since March 8 in
some of the most savage artillery and rocket battles of Lebanon's
14-year civil war.
   About 360 people have been killed and nearly 1,400 wounded,
mostly civilians.
   The Christians are tired and dispirited, struggling to cope with
a grim fatalism.
   The cease-fire, violated daily by the Syrians, had raised
people's hopes they would be able to pick up the pieces of their
shattered lives and find some semblance of normality.
   Instead, there's a stillness punctuated only by the periodic
crump of exploding shells.
   The Syrians maintain their blockade of the Christian enclave,
ringed on its landward sides by hostile Moslem forces.
   Small cargo ships run the gauntlet of shellfire to bring in food
and ammunition for the besieged Christians. Until a few days ago,
the blockade runners didn't try bringing in gas.
   ``It only takes one hit to blow up a ship loaded with fuel,'' a
police spokesman said. ``So no one dares take the risk.''
   One small tanker, the 1,507-ton Chemicoral, made a run Thursday
with 660,000 gallons of gasoline. But it was hit by Syrian shellfire
and its cargo burned.
   Others than gas, there are no real shortages, thanks to the
blockade runners.
   Supermarkets bulge with imported goods _ pink chamapagne, passion
fruit tea, whisky, cookies, chocolates, hams, cheeses.
   Fruit and vegetables are in short supply, but available for a
price. Before the fighting, most produce came from Syrian-controlled
areas. Now they're smuggled in at night by muletrain from the north.
   The enclave's fuel reserves went up in flames when a Syrian
barrage blew up the seaside Dora depot in east Beirut two months ago.
   The French, Lebanon's colonial rulers until 1943 and the
Christians' traditional protector, shipped in 4,000 tons of fuel to
reactivate shut-down power plants a few weeks ago.
   There's so little gasoline around that only about one-fifth of
the filling stations bother to open.
   Police said two people have been killed and 10 wounded in
gunfights over gas.
   ``People have to wait for days in front of the stations and all
they get in the end is 10 liters (2.25 gallons),'' one attendant
said.
   A half-tank at filling stations costs $50, a month's wages for
many Lebanese.
   One motorist noted: ``Filling station owners pump out the gas
from their tanks and sell it on the black market for 10 times the
price.''
   Long lines of cars, some extending a mile, stand outside many
filling stations.
   ``At first, everyone used to wait for days in their cars, even
during the shelling,'' grocer Samir Madi said. ``Now we take it in
turns to wait for a station to open.
   ``When it does, whoever's keeping vigil telephones everyone else
and they all rush to the station.''
   Bank clerk Samar Moallem, who earns $60 a month, hasn't gone to
work for weeks.
   ``I don't have any gas,'' she said. ``I can't afford to pay my
whole salary for 20 liters or pay ($2 a day) for taxis getting to
and from work. I told the bank if they want me they'll have to get
me gas.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
