<DOCNO> AP890617-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0536EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CatholicBishops     06-17 0627</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Catholic Bishops,0643</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishops Consider Support of Renewed Relations With Vietnam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Catholic Catholic Church is
trying to heal the wounds left by the Vietnam War, but some bishops
fear support of renewed relations with Vietnam may grant legitimacy
to its communist government.
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops was scheduled to vote
today on a proposal for normalizing relations with Vietnam.
   The Committee on International Policy of the United States
Catholic Conference is recommending the church support the proposal.
The annual spring meeting of the nation's bishops opened Friday at
Seton Hall University with debate on the proposal by the committee,
which visited with Vietnamese bishops in January.
   Archbishop Roger M. Mahony, committee chairman, said the
committee did not seek to express approval of the Vietnamese regime,
but to work for improved relations that could lead to increased
humanitarian assistance and a more effective forum for expressing
concerns over violations of human rights and religious liberty.
   But some bishops said Vietnamese Americans are concerned the
church is granting legitimacy to a ``barbaric'' regime in return for
vague promises.
   Bishop Joseph J. Madera of Fresno, Calif., said the brother of a
priest in his diocese has spent 30 years in a Vietnamese prison.
   ``We have to hear not just the bishops of Vietnam, but also the
people who are affected in their daily lives,'' he said.
   Also Friday, the conference president declared relations have
never been better in recent years between the Vatican and the church
in the United States.
   ``I believe that the bridge between Rome and the United States is
stronger than it has been in recent memory,'' said Archbishop John
L. May of St. Louis.
   Archbishop Pio Laghi, the apostolic pro-nuncio who is the pope's
representative in the United States, agreed with May.
   ``Now we have a very good relationship,'' Laghi said. ``There is
a beautiful atmosphere now, very warm.''
   May said after his talk that ``a lot of eyes and a lot of ears''
have been opened in Rome following a series of encounters with U.S.
bishops, including the pope's visit in 1987, meetings with
individual bishops last year, and a March meeting of cardinals and
archbishops with Vatican officials.
   Other bishops agreed there is a new era in relations with the
Vatican.
   ``We all learned from our experiences,'' said Cardinal Joseph
Bernardin of Chicago, who helped resolve a dispute involving Seattle
Archbishop Raymond Hunthausen, who was unilaterally stripped by the
Vatican of some of his ecclesial authority for alleged doctrinal
abuses. Most of his authority was later restored after U.S. bishops
intervened.
   In a test of their new relationship, the bishops were scheduled
to vote today on a document that proposes ways to resolve disputes
between bishops and theologians. The proposal from the bishops'
Committee on Doctrine has been criticized by the Vatican for
appearing to place bishops and theologians on equal levels.
   In March, the Congregation for the Doctrine of the Faith in Rome,
said the proposed document on ``Doctrinal Responsibilities,'' which
advocates the ``rights'' of theologians to lawful freedom of inquiry
and expression of scholarly opinion, ``tends logically to the
erection of a second teaching authority in the Church.''
   Today, the committee of bishops was also to present a progress
report on an AIDS policy that will be debated and voted on at a
future conference. It had been planned months ago to present the
report and open it up to debate and a possible vote at the Seton
Hall conference, said the Rev. Kenneth Doyle spokesman for the
conference.
   He said, however, that the report was not far enough along to be
debated, and the report would consist only of an estimated timetable
for its completion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
