<DOCNO> AP890617-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0539EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     06-17 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>DOE Announces Improved Monitoring of Rocky Flats Plutonium Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department plans to commit $1.8 million
a year to improve monitoring of the troubled Rocky Flats plutonium
plant and to purchase $730,000 worth of monitoring equipment.
   The federal government also assured Gov. Roy Romer on Friday that
the state will be able to independently monitor activity at the
plant, which is under investigation for safety violations.
   The promise was part of an agreement reached by Energy Department
Deputy Director Henson Moore and Romer following the governor's
threat last week to shut down the plant.
   At a news conference, Moore and Romer announced the agreement,
which must be ratified by Energy Secretary James Watkins.
   ``We are going to operate on the basis that people need to know
the truth, and we are going to get it to them in a way in which it
is verified independently of the operation of the plant,'' Romer
said. ``My policy has been we've got to clean it up _ or close it
down.''
   Rocky Flats, located 16 miles northwest of Denver, manufactures
plutonium detonators for nuclear bombs. Rockwell International
operates the plant for the Energy Department.
   On June 6, scores of FBI agents and Environmental Protection
Agency investigators raided the plant looking for evidence of
illegal dumping and incineration of hazardous wastes.
   The on-site investigation continued Friday.
   Under Friday's agreement, the Energy Department will provide
additional technical and financial support for state environmental
oversight, monitoring, repair, emergency response and health-related
initiatives.
   The department said it will accelerate cleanup where
contamination presents a threat. It also will monitor surface waters
and treated drinking water, streams entering reservoirs, samples of
discharges and underground water under the agreement.
   Moore said the Bush administration wants to send the message that
``environment, safety and health is not any longer `a factor' _ it
is the first priority in the operation of any of our facilities.''
   The department will consent to penalties ``if we don't live up to
the agreement with the governor's office,'' said Moore.
   Asked about the department's historical ``lack of candor'' about
reporting incidents at the plant, Moore snapped at a reporter: ``I
don't lie to people, fella! Not to you, not to him (the governor),
not to anybody else. You just watch what we do.''
   He said if Rockwell ``cannot assure the plant is being run in a
safe manner ... then they are not to produce,'' he said.
   Sam F. Iacobellis, president of Rockwell International Aerospace
Operations, hailed the agreement. ``We have long urged similar
actions and fully support the governor's initiative,'' he said.
   He also denied allegations in an FBI affidavit that Rocky Flats
illegally operated an incinerator at night in a building closed by
Energy Department inspectors. Iacobellis also said there was no
deliberate ``midnight dumping'' of wastes at Rocky Flats.
   Energy Department officials said Friday that new tests show
drinking water in northwest metropolitan Denver is uncontaminated by
chemicals the FBI suspects were dumped into creeks at Rocky Flats.
Some of the creeks empty into reservoirs used as municipal water
supplies.
   Romer earlier threatened to close the plant unless the department
stepped up its environmental monitoring at the site and made the
results available to him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
