<FIRST>r a PM-DeltaTurbulence     06-17 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Delta Turbulence,0459</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delta Flight Hits Turbulence, Seven Hospitalized</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Delta Air Lines jetliner en route to Atlanta hit
turbulence that sent passengers flying and seven people were
hospitalized, most with broken bones.
   About 25 people were taken to four hospitals after Delta Flight
102 hit air turbulence over Alabama, about 200 miles northwest of
Atlanta. All but seven were treated and released. The L-1011 was
carrying 282 passengers from Seattle to Hartsfield Atlanta
International Airport.
   The plane was at about 25,000 feet when the turbulence occurred.
It landed at Hartsfield Airport about 3:45 p.m. Friday, said Delta
spokesman Jim Lundy.
   Passengers on the flight said the pilot told them at the start of
the trip that it was his last flight after 33 years of flying.
   One of the plane's uninjured passengers, Linda Alexander of
Seattle, said that only those who weren't wearing seat belts were in
danger.
   ``As it (the plane) dropped, anyone not fastened in went up and a
lot of people were flying through the air,'' she said.
   Delta spokeswoman Glenda Hatchett Johnson said the seat-belt
light was on at the time.
   ``The kids were screaming and the food was flying and the people
were flying,'' said Brenda Chevalier of Seattle, who was treated for
a sprained back.
   ``It's like you're on a roller coaster and at the top of a hill,
the way your stomach feels,'' she said. ``We dropped thousands of
feet. There's no control _ you've lost it. I thought I was going to
die. I kept screaming, `God, please be with us.' ''
   Federal Aviation Administration spokesman Jack Barker said that
although passengers felt they were falling a great distance, ``it
was probably more like a two-second free fall that seemed like 20
seconds.''
   The FAA had no measurement of how far the plane fell.
   Ann Renner, a spokeswoman at South Fulton Hospital, said one
passenger was admitted to the hospital's intensive care unit in
serious condition with broken ribs and four others were being kept
at the hospital, most for broken bones. She would not identify any
of the patients.
   A Shallowford Hospital official said one passenger was
hospitalized in stable condition with a concussion. Another was
being kept for observation at Georgia Baptist Hospital.
   The hospitals treated and released other passengers Friday night.
   Ms. Johnson said several more passengers were treated by
paramedics at the airport for bruises.
   Meantime, passengers aboard a Northwest Airlines flight en route
from Seattle to Detroit on Friday remained calm and were uninjured
during an unscheduled landing in Bismarck, N.D., after the
twin-engine Boeing 757 developed an oil leak in an engine. The plane
carried 182 passengers.
</TEXT>
