<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-Americans     06-17 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-Americans,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rebels Followed Americans for Possible Assassination, Report Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels shadowed nine U.S.
servicemen assigned to Clark Air Base last year, apparently in
preparation for an assassination attempt, it was reported today.
   The Pacific Stars and Stripes, an unofficial U.S. military
newspaper, quoted Filipino authorities in Angeles City as saying
they learned of the surveillance through documents captured last
July from the communist New People's Army.
   According to the report, the rebels watched two U.S. Air Force
colonels, a lieutenant colonel, four captains, and two sergeants
assigned to the base in Angeles City.
   The newspaper quoted police Maj. Efren Alamares as saying the
nine were apparently targeted because they lived off post.
   Efforts to contact police in Angeles City were unsuccesful
because telephone lines there were out of order.
   Philippine rebels have sometimes attacked Americans in the past.
   Last April, they killed U.S. Army Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe as he
drove to work at the Joint U.S. Military Assistance Group in the
Manila suburb of Quezon City.
   In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino
civilian in coordinated ambushes outside Clark.
   The rebels have repeatedly threatened attacks on U.S. personnel
because of Washington's support of President Corazon Aquino's
counterinsurgency campaign.
   Capt. Donna Eggelston, Clark spokeswoman, said the Air Force
``periodically receives intelligence reports on terrorist activity.
   ``The report in question concerns information received in 1988,''
she said. ``Due to the sensitive nature of these reports, we do not
comment on them, and we do this to protect individuals who may be
involved.''
   She refused to say whether the nine personnel are still assigned
to Clark or to describe their duties.
   About 40,000 American troops, civilians and military dependents
are stationed at six U.S. military installations in the Philippines.
   More than half are stationed at Clark in central Luzon, the main
Philippine island. Rebels are strong in the area.
   The New People's Army has been waging a 20-year insurgency to
establish a Marxist state.
</TEXT>
