<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0611EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NoMoreHomesteading     06-17 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-No More Homesteading,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>County To Dismantle Its Homesteading Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INTERNATIONAL FALLS, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A northern Minnesota county is
withdrawing its offer of free land to would-be homesteaders because
of complaints from longtime residents and legal and financial snags.
   Commissioners of Koochiching County decided this week to stop
taking applications for land after Sept. 1, almost three years
earlier than planned.
   ``It hasn't been a failure at all,'' said Commissioner Larry
Chezick. ``I just don't think we ever had visions of how the media
would portray this.''
   The rural county along the Canadian border began the program two
years ago, hoping that up to 40 acres of free land would attract
modern-day pioneers and offset declines in population, school
enrollment and the local economy.
   It is believed to be the first such land-giveaway since the 19th
century federal homesteading program that populated much of the
nation, and it attracted intense coverage from newspapers, magazines
and television stations around the globe that didn't want to miss a
once-in-a-century story.
   In the wake of the publicity whirlwind, more than 10,000 people
asked for information about the program from across the country and
as far afield as Europe and Japan. Hundreds visited the county to
scout for a homestead and more than 250 submitted applications.
   Last winter, three homesteading hopefuls from Colorado were
arrested trying to break into an empty farmhouse. Another time, two
Germans wandered into the local Job Service office, saying they
intended to homestead and needed work.
   As a result, some of the county's slightly more than 16,000
residents complained that the giveaway would attract too many
undesireables to the area.
   The county also had to take back initial claims that 50,000 acres
of tax-forfeited county and state land were available because some
of the state land was held in trust.
   So far only two homesteads have been awarded, going to local men
who applied before the flood of outside interest. But one of the two
said he had trouble getting a loan to build a house. He couldn't use
his land as collateral because homesteaders only receive title to
their property after living on it for 10 years.
   Under the plan to halt the program this fall, at least 25 but no
more than 100 applicants will be given land. Jerry Andre, the
program administrator, said there are about 20 more applicants that
are likely to be approved.
   The county's disenchantment with the program has done little to
dampen the curiosity of people who want to homestead. ``They're
still coming through, more than ever,'' Andre said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890617-0038 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ChannelOne     06-17 0537</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Channel One,0551</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regents Ban ``Channel One'' From New York Classrooms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A commercially sponsored TV show has been
banned from the state's high schools, dealing a second big blow to
the company that hopes to beam a daily newscast into the nation's
classrooms.
   The New York Board of Regents unanimously rejected Whittle
Communications' ``Channel One'' program Friday, saying they were
worried the ``active commercialization'' of the programs would send
the wrong message to high school students.
   ``It's a very tempting package that has a flaw,'' said state
Education Commissioner Thomas Sobol. ``That flaw is that it's wrong.
It's wrong legally, educationally, financially and morally.''
   Some regents also expressed anger with Whittle's aggressive
lobbying in support of ``Channel One.'' Edward Meyer charged that
some members of the education policy-setting board told him Whittle
had offered them jobs or consulting contracts if they supported the
project.
   Laura Eshbaugh, executive vice president for Whittle
Communications, said she knew nothing about any offers.
   Knoxville, Tenn.-based Whittle has said it needs to sign up 40
percent of the nation's high schools if ``Channel One'' is to
succeed. The first severe blow to that goal was delivered earlier
this month, when California officials threatened their schools with
a loss of funds if they signed with Whittle.
   Eshbaugh said she was disappointed with the New York board's
decision, but said ``Channel One'' would survive the rejection.
   Whittle had increased its offer to the regents and taken its case
to the public in the days leading to Friday's board meeting. The
company ran full-page advertisements in The New York Times and Meyer
said some Regents were bombarded by ``junk fax'' messages in support
of Whittle.
   In return for an agreement to show the daily programs, Whittle
had offered to wire high schools with complete closed-circuit
television systems, including satellite dishes, televisions and
videocassette recorders.
   As the regents' decision approached, Whittle officials offered to
donate 1,000 hours of satellite time so other educational
programming could be shown in schools, education department
officials said.
   But Whittle wouldn't change the most debated aspect of its
program: The 12-minute news program still had to contain two minutes
of commercials for candy, jeans, acne cream and other products aimed
at teen-agers.
   ``What it says to children is we don't care much about you,''
Sobol said, ``but we care what we can get out of you.''
   Several regents said they worried the commercials could cause
poor students who couldn't afford items advertised to feel
inadequate. They also said the program seems geared to suburban,
white students instead of the more troubled city schools that are in
dire need of the technology Whittle could provide.
   But Eshbaugh noted that schools contain many other forms of
advertising, such as wall posters, advertisements in yearbooks and
magazines and brand names emblazoned on the clothing students wear.
   ``Commercialization is there,'' she said. ``However any of us
might not like it there, it's there to stay.''
   The regents said the discussion with Whittle has caused them to
examine the extent of other advertising in school. The Education
Department will also look into other ways of getting more technology
and television programs into school, Sobol said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
