<FIRST>r a PM-FernaldTrial     06-17 0489</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fernald Trial,0502</SECOND>
<HEAD>Energy Department Undecided on Fernald Settlement After Losing Mock
Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Energy Department officials intend to decide
whether a jury's ruling should prompt settlement of a lawsuit by the
Fernald uranium processing plant's neighbors, but a department
spokesmen declined to say when.
   In Washington, Energy Department spokesman Will Callicott was
non-committal Friday following a U.S. District Court jury's
non-binding recommendation that neighbors of the Feed Materials
Production Center be awarded $136 million in damages.
   The jury issued its ruling Thursday in the mock trial of a
class-action suit filed by 14,000 neighbors of the plant, which
processes uranium used in making the government's nuclear weapons.
   Neighbors claimed radioactive emissions from the plant have
damaged their health and the environment and lowered property values.
   The eight-member jury's verdict ended a summary jury trial, an
abbreviated procedure that Judge S. Arthur Spiegel used to encourage
a settlement of the neighbors' lawsuit against the former operator
of the Energy Department plant.
   Energy Department lawyer Henry Gill Jr. refused to say whether
the jury verdict would prompt a settlement offer. The residents'
lawyer, Stanley Chesley, said he would consider such an offer.
   Callicott said Gill was not due back in Washington until Monday,
and that Gill would have to confer with top department managers.
   The jury ruled that National Lead of Ohio Inc. operated the Feed
Materials Production Center in a way that caused neighbors to suffer
the distress and lowered property values they had claimed.
   The company operated the plant 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati
under contract to the federal government from 1951 through 1985.
Also named as a defendant was its parent company, National Lead
Industries Inc.
   The Energy Department defended the companies, arguing that they
could not be found liable because they carried out the government's
directions. The department admitted in documents filed with the
court that the government sometimes told National Lead of Ohio
managers to emphasize production and not to worry about
environmental protection or regulations.
   Gill said any settlement of the case would be paid by the
government because of an indemnification clause in its contract with
the operator. If there is no settlement, the case goes to a real
trial Aug. 15 before Spiegel, who presided at the shortened summary
trial.
   Chesley, representing the 14,000 plaintiffs who live within five
miles of the plant, said the jury's verdict amounted to a total
victory.
   Residents said in their lawsuit that radioactive contamination
from the plant has polluted soil, air and water, causing them mental
stress and making their homes undesirable.
   The Energy Department estimates that 383,000 pounds of
radioactive uranium oxide dust has been released from faulty
exhaust-air filters since the plant opened. Government lawyers said
the material has not endangered residents or harmed property.
   Westinghouse Materials Co. of Ohio, which has operated the plant
since January 1986, is not a defendant in the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
