<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Slaying     06-17 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Slaying,0420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Official Denies Involvement in Journalist's Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former security chief accused in the murder
of an investigative journalist denied involvement in the slaying,
saying he wouldn't have rushed to the scene of the crime if he had
ordered the killing.
   Jose Antonio Zorrilla, 47, spoke with reporters after a witness
to the slaying of Manuel Buendia testified that he saw a man who
resembled the killer go into office of the Federal Security
Department days after the May 30, 1985, murder.
   Zorrilla, chief of the FBI-like department from 1982-84, listened
from behind bars in the courtroom for three hours while a court
official read Juan Manuel Bautista Ortiz, who was Buendia's office
aide, statements he had earlier made to authorities.
   Under questioning by the prosecutor Rafael Avanzi, Bautista said
the man he saw ``100 percent resembled'' the killer.
   During his testimony, Bautista also said Zorrilla arrived at the
scene with agents from his office about 15 minutes after Buendia was
shot, Bautista said.
   ``I was not going to be naive enough to go there immediately to
see what happened if I had been responsible,'' Zorrilla said. ``I
would have said `I'm not going.' It would have been infantile to go
to the place where it happened.''
   He said he was a friend of the journalist and went
target-shooting with him.
   Zorrilla pleaded innocent at his arraignment Thursday before
Judge Roberto Hernandez Martinez of Mexico City's 34th Penal Court
on homicide charges. Prosecutors have said he was the mastermind of
the crime.
   The judge has until Sunday to decide if the case has merit and
return a formal indictment.
   Zorrilla faces 40 years in prison on the homicide charge and 22
years on other accusations, including abuse of authority and weapons
charges.
   The former security security chief said he believed Buendia was
killed because of the front-page columns he wrote for the newspaper
Excelsior.
   He said he ``had touched on very delicate subjects.''
   In columns and books, Buendia wrote on corruption in high places,
drug trafficking, the CIA and gun-running.
   Witnesses questioned during the murder investigation also linked
Zorrilla to drug trafficking and Mexican narcotics kingpin Rafael
Caro Quintero. Zorrilla has denied such ties.
   Caro Quintero is awaiting trial in the killing of U.S. Drug
Enforcement Administration agent Enrique Camarena Salazar and his
Mexican pilot Alfredo Zavala Avelar in Guadalajara in 1985.
</TEXT>
