<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     06-17 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>More Storms in East, Contribute to Four Deaths</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms continued to lash the East Coast, contributing to
at least four deaths, causing flooding in three states and knocking
out power to more than 100,000 consumers in South Carolina.
   Eight tornadoes were sighted in North Carolina and one in South
Carolina Friday, but no injuries or serious damages were reported
from the twisters. Hurricane-force winds gusting to 78 mph were
recorded in South Carolina.
   Winds downed trees and power lines, leaving an estimated 90,000
customers without power in the Columbia area and another 10,000 to
15,000 customers without power in other parts of the state, said
Brian Duncan, a spokesman for South Carolina Electric &amp; Gas Co.
   Duke Power Co. spokeswoman Mary Boyd said about 12,000 customers
were without power around Lancaster, Great Falls and Kershaw.
   Claudius W. Pender, 67, was killed when a tree fell on his truck
in Columbia, Richland County Chief Deputy Coroner Jim Anasti said.
   Elflist Nathaniel Smith, 21, was killed when a utility pole
crushed the roof of a car in which he was riding from Greensboro to
his hometown of Raleigh, authorities said.
   Rain swollen rivers and creeks wiped out bridges, chewed up
roads, flooded homes and contributed to two deaths in eastern
Kentucky, where up to five inches of rain fell Thursday and Friday.
At least 120 families were forced to seek dry ground, state
officials said.
   In Breathitt County, a 32-year-old man jumped into the
rain-swollen Kentucky River and was swept away. And in Madison
County, a 31-year-old man died after a car ran off a road and landed
in a swollen creek.
   In West Virginia, storms drove rivers up by as much as 14 feet
Friday and forced officials to evacuate the town of Dunlow and close
several highways.
   In Montgomery, Ala., where 6 inches of rain fell in four days,
firefighters used a boat Friday to rescue a bedridden woman and four
children from a wood-frame house, and several bridges on dirt roads
were ashed out in Geneva County.
   Thunderstorm winds also downed trees and power lines in central
Florida and Virginia.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued this morning from central
Florida to central North Carolina, with the strongest storms in
southeast Georgia.
   Showeres were numerous from the upper Ohio Valley and lower Great
Lakes into western New England. Dense fog was reported in Rhode
Island.
   Elsewhere, thunderstorms produced baseball-size hail and wind
gusts to 76 mph in Wyoming Friday evening, and storm winds gusted to
71 mph at Rapid City, S.D.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued across central South Dakota
and western Nebraska early this morning, and over parts of the
southern Plains.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms in the East
Coast, and from the northern and central Appalachians to Michigan.
Showers and thunderstorms also were forecast for the northern and
central Plains, Missouri and Oklahoma. Rain was expected across the
Pacific Northwest.
   Predicted highs: 70s and 80s in most of the nation; 60s in the
Pacific Northwest and parts of Michigan; 90s in Florida, and from
southwest Texas across New Mexico and southern Arizona to
California's interior valleys, with parts of southwest Texas getting
above 100 degrees; and up to 115 degrees in the desert Southwest.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 35 degrees at Yellowstone
Park, Wyo., to 94 at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 68 partly cloudy; Boston 68 partly cloudy; Buffalo
56 rain; Charleston, S.C. 75 cloudy; Cincinnati 53 fair; Cleveland
55 fair; Detroit 49 fair; Miami 81 partly cloudy; New York 66 windy;
Philadelphia 70 partly cloudy; Pittsburgh 60 foggy; Portland, Maine
54 cloudy; Washington 70 wind.
   _Central: Bismarck 62 showery; Chicago 55 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth
68 fair; Denver 68 windy; Des Moines 61 fair; Indianapolis 50 fair;
Kansas City 59 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 56 fair; Nashville 59
foggy; New Orleans 65 fair; St. Louis 64 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 71 cloudy; Anchorage 55 fair; Las Vegas 84
fair; Los Angeles 61 fair; Phoenix 94 partly cloudy; Salt Lake City
58 fair; San Diego 62 fair; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 57 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 57 showery; Toronto 55 foggy.
</TEXT>
