<FIRST>r i PM-China-Britain     06-17 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Britain,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>China Expresses `Deep Regret' to Britain Over Hong Kong Issue</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China expressed ``deep regret'' to Britain today
for delaying a meeting on the transition of Hong Kong to Chinese
rule.
   Britain put off the session of the Sino-British Joint Liaison
Group on the future of Hong Kong, originally scheduled for next
month in London, to protest China's suppression of the pro-democracy
student movement. No new date has been set.
   In reaction, China said today that Britain ``will be held
responsible for all possible consequences.''
   The Foreign Ministry in its statement said it hopes Britain
remains committed to handing over Hong Kong in 1997 under an
agreement made in 1984, but added, ``We express our deep regret over
this irresponsible action taken by the British government.''
   Britain's Foreign Office has said it will honor the accord but
cannot conduct normal business at the moment ``as if nothing had
happened.''
   The pact returns Hong Kong to China in eight years but guarantees
that China will not interfere with its capitalist system for at
least 50 years.
   The current suppression of dissent on the mainland has raised
anxieties in the British colony about Chinese rule. Many Hong Kong
residents have demanded that Britain allow more of them to resettle
there.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher said resettling all 3.25 million
British passport holders in Hong Kong is politically impossible. She
has instead pledged greater flexibility in existing arrangements,
particularly for those who worked for the British government.
   The Joint Liaison Group is supposed to meet three times a year to
work out details of the transition. Its second meeting this year had
been scheduled for July 18-21.
</TEXT>
