<FIRST>r i PM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0449 06-17 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0449,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinians in Occupied Territories Begin General Strike</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with reports of clashes, raid by
soldiers. Pickup 3rd graf pvs, `Prime Minister...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinians in the occupied territories
launched another general strike today to protest Israel's Middle
East peace plan.
   According to Arab reports, the strike shut down the Gaza Strip
and principal West Bank cities.
   There were scattered clashes, and an 18-year-old Palestinian was
reported wounded in the West Bank, Arab reports said. They said the
army conducted raids on the West Bank villages of Osarin and Hawara
near Nablus, and about two dozen residents were reported beaten with
assault rifles.
   A Palestinian reporter in Gaza City, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said youths burned tires in the streets and threw rocks
at military vehicles.
   Strike pamphlets issued by the underground leaders of the
18-month uprising said the action was ``to call on the American
administration to hold an international conference, as it is the
only way to reach peace in the region.''
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's peace plan calls for Palestinian
elections in the West Bank and Gaza to be followed by negotiations
with the elected reprsentatives on a form of limited self-rule.
   He opposes a proposed international peace conference that would
be sponsored by the United Nations and would include the Middle East
parties directly involved and also the United States and Soviet
Union. Shamir has said such a conference would be biased against
Israel and demand territorial concessions that would jeopardize the
Jewish state.
   There was scattered violence in the occupied territories Friday.
   Arab reports said Israeli soldiers, battling stone-throwing
Palestinians in the Gaza town of Rafah, opened fire, killing three
people.
   Hospital officials in Rafah said 13 Arabs were wounded in the
clashes.
   The deaths raised to 520 the number of Palestinians killed in the
uprising that began in December 1987. Twenty-two Israelis have
perished in the violence.
   Reports identified the three slain men as Valid Omar Abu Abed,
23, Amir Fuad Nasser, 25, and 17-year-old Ahmed Abed Rabbo Abu Oun.
They said all three died from gunshot wounds.
   An Arab reporter in Jafah said the violence ``began with small
clashes after the (noon Moslem) prayers ... Then Abu Abed was killed
and protests escalated.''
   Shooting was heard in Rafah hours after dark and army
reinforcements were sent in.
   Rafah is under an indefinite curfew with the 50,000 residents
ordered to remain inside their homes.
   Four other Arabs were reported shot and wounded in clashes with
troops elsewhere in the Gaza Strip and the West Strip.
   Arab doctors said a 60-year-old Palestinian woman was wounded by
a rubber bullet and two Arab youths suffered injuries when they were
beaten during a battle outside a Gaza City detention center.
   An army spokesman said dozens of Palestinians waiting to visit
their jailed relatives rioted after being told the prisoners were on
a hunger strike and refused to see visitors. He said people outside
began throwing stones when they heard a shot fired inside the prison
to quiet unruly detainees and troops moved in to quell the
disturbance.
</TEXT>
