<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0902EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Ireland 2ndLd-Writethru   06-17 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ireland, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0459,0742</SECOND>
<HEAD>Haughey Concedes Opposition Left Gains in Ireland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 17 grafs to UPDATE with Haughey comment, new returns.
Pickup 18th pvs, ``This is...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Charles Haughey conceded
today he had not won a majority in parliament in the Irish general
election but said he would attempt to form a government.
   ``I didn't get the answer I wanted,'' Haughey said.
   With more than 90 percent of the seats decided after Thursday's
election, it was clear that Haughey would have to govern with fewer
friendly faces. The results prompted talk of a historic realignment
of Irish politics.
   ``One of the disappointing things is that Irish politics may now
become polarized between right and left,'' said Progressive
Democrats leader Desmond O'Malley.
   Nonetheless, Haughey said he had no intention of resigning as
leader of the Fianna Fail Party, the country's largest.
   ``We will form a government,'' he said. ``We will do our
political best to provide the people with a government.''
   National election returns early today showed a surge of the Irish
left, with the Labor Party and the Workers Party gaining seats, and
the Green Party getting into Ireland's parliament, called the Dail,
for the first time.
   The state television network RTE projected that Fianna Fail would
win 77 or 78 seats, a loss of two or three.
   With 151 of 165 races decided, Fianna Fail had won 70 seats, Fine
Gael 47, Labor Party 15, Progressive Democrats 6, Workers Party 7,
Democratic Socialist 1, Green Party 1, independent and others 4.
Recounts were under way in six constituencies.
   It was a sharp setback for Haughey, who called the vote hoping to
gain his first majority in five elections. During his previous four
terms, he governed with support from other parties.
   ``It's quite clear that you can't impose stringent financial
policies which are unpopular and expect people to give you the sort
of majority we were looking for,'' he said in an RTE interview.
   Haughey had steeply reduced Ireland's budget deficit but at a
cost of sharp cuts in social services. He admitted during the
campaign he was surprised at the ferocity of resentment especially
against health service cuts.
   Asked why he had called the election, Haughey said ``it was a
political judgment'' that his support in parliament from the
opposition Fine Gael Party ``wasn't going to last any longer, and I
was anxious to get a working majority so that I could go ahead and
implement our very comprehensive national development plan.''
   Fine Gael leader Alan Dukes derided Haughey as a ``five-time
loser.''
   Though he had predicted earlier in the week that his party would
win the election, Dukes said today he was ``very happy'' with his
modest gains.
   Fianna Fail (Soldiers of Destiny) and Fine Fael (Family of the
Irish) are both conservative economically, but Fine Gael tends to be
more liberal on social issues. The Progressive Democrats are
breakaways from Fianna Fail.
   The left, meanwhile, exulted in its victories.
   ``This is the best day we (the left) have had in the history of
the state,'' said Jim Kemmy, a surprise winner in east Limerick. He
will be the only Democratic Socialist in the Dail.
   ``We're talking about the left breaking the mold,'' said Paty
Rabbittee, a winner for the Workers Party in southwest Dublin.
   James Downey, editor of The New Nation magazine, said Haughey's
party, Fianna Fail, had itself to blame for the leftist surge.
   ``Fianna Fail ... did something that they have never ever done
before. They made a choice between middle-class and working-class
vote, and they got the middle-class vote,'' Downey said Friday night.
   Haughey's program of fiscal austerity won approval from the
middle class, but cuts in health services apparently hurt its
support among the working class.
   Gerry O'Sullivan of the Labor Party, who won in north-central
Cork, said a hospital closing was a factor in his victory.
   Despite the disappointment for Haughey, the next term would still
mark the first time he has served twice in a row. He was beaten
after all his other terms.
   Fianna Fail claims the mantle of forces that originally opposed
the partition of Ireland in 1921. Its nationalism has kept it in
power for most of the republic's 68-year history.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
