<FIRST>r a PM-CoalStrike 1stLd-Writethru a0439 06-17 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coal Strike, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0439,0512</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coal Strike Expands to Six States</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to add Tennessee, sixth state.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Mine Workers wildcat strike
that grew during the week to include more than 20,000 miners in six
states shows no sign of ending, UMW officials say.
   ``We're having trouble keeping them in the mines,'' said Roger
Myers, international executive board member for UMW District 11 in
Indiana.
   On Friday, the wildcat walkout idled 2,500 miners in
Pennsylvania, 1,390 in Indiana, 790 in Virginia, 295 in Kentucky,
200 in Tennessee and about two-thirds of West Virginia's 24,000
miners, company officials said.
   At AMAX Coal Co.'s Ayrshire Mine at Chandler, Ind., UMW Local
1907 President Greg Young said after a union meeting Friday that
workers will continue to strike, although he told them the UMW
constitution and contract require them to return to work.
   West Virginia Gov. Gaston Caperton said he ``is continuing every
day in a quiet, behind-the-scenes way talking to both sides to see
what we can do in state government to bring this to an end.''
   The walkout began Monday in southern West Virginia in sympathy
with about 1,600 UMW members on strike against the Pittston Coal
Group in West Virginia and Virginia.
   The original strike by West Virginia and Virginia miners began in
April when Pittston dropped out of the Bituminous Coal Operators
Association to negotiate with the union independently. The two sides
have failed to reach an agreement despite 16 months of negotiations.
   In Pennsylvania, District 2 President Nick Molnar said union
officials planned to tell each of the 52 local unions that their
members should report to work as usual. Molnar said he could not
predict whether the miners would obey.
   Molnar was among union leaders who led a Friday morning rally by
about 5,000 miners in Ebensburg, Pa., near Johnstown.
   Molnar said the miners supported striking Pittston workers and
criticized the court system which, he said, is ``practicing economic
terrorism against the mine workers' organization.''
   In Hazleton, Pa., meanwhile, District 25 officials are organizing
miners who could leave on short notice from UMW President Richard
Trumka to picket in support of the Pittston strikers, said Bill Ray,
District 25 president and an acting member of the union's
international executive board.
   On Friday, U.S. District Judge William Kidd in Clarksburg issued
back-to-work orders for seven Consolidation Coal Co. mines in
northern West Virginia. Striking miners have ignored similar orders
in southern West Virginia all week.
   The strikers Friday included about 1,600 miners who failed to
report for work at Rochester &amp; Pittsburgh Coal Co. operations in
central Pennsylvania, company spokesman Hank Waneck said.
   ``We are being penalized for a labor problem in another area. It
appears that the United Mine Workers are returning to the era of
instability of the 1970s, which contributed to the decline of UMW
mined coal from 70 percent to less than 35 percent of the nation's
production today,'' Waneck said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
