<DOCNO> AP890617-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1003EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Yugoslavia     06-17 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Yugoslavia,0377</SECOND>
<HEAD>Amendment Gives Slovenia Right to Secede From Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Slovenia's Parliament has adopted a
constitutional amendment granting this nation's most developed
republic the right to secede, news reports said today.
   The amendment, which was passed on Friday, states that the
Slovenian people have ``the lasting and inalienable right to
self-determination, including the right to secession and
association,'' the official Tanjug news agency said.
   It was unlikely, however, that federal authorities in Belgrade
would allow the northern republic to break away from the union.
   Yugoslavia, a loose federaration of six republics and two
provinces containing various nationalities and religions, is passing
through its worst economic and political crisis. Annual inflation
exceeds 600 percent, and there has been an alarming increase in
social and ethnic tension.
   The republic of Slovenia, whose leadership advocates regional
autonomy, greater democracy and closer ties with the West, has long
been at odds with the southern republic of Serbia, where officials
favor greater central control and a stronger federal government.
Slovenia's Communist Party leadership is considered the most liberal
in Yugoslavia.
   The clash between the two republics, characterized by official
media as a propaganda campaign between two countries at war, has
generated Serbian and Slovenian nationalist feelings.
   In an unusually blunt interview published Friday, Slovenia's
Communist Party chief Milan Kucan said relations between the
republics are ``frozen.''
   ``We have to decide if we want to continue living together or
not,'' Kucan was quoted as saying. He said co-existence should not
be ``at any cost.''
   Slavko Goldstein, president of the Croatian Social-Liberal Union,
an independent group, has said the ruling Communist Party cannot
solve Yugoslavia's crisis. Only an agreement among ``non-communist
forces'' can prevent the country from falling apart, he said.
   Yugoslavia's Communist leadership is split between ``two
irreconcilable political concepts'' _ Slovenian and Serbian _ which
could cause a civil war, similar to that in Lebanon, he said.
   Kosovo, a province of Serbia, has been torn by ethnic strife.
   In March, 25 people were killed when ethnic Albanians rioted to
protest constitutional changes giving Serbia more control over the
province. In Kosovo, 85 percent of the 1.8 million inhabitants are
ethnic Albanians.
</TEXT>
