<FIRST>r i PM-NorthernIreland     06-17 0296</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northern Ireland,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Protestants, One Catholic Injured In Sectarian Attacks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three Protestants and a Roman
Catholic were seriously injured in sectarian attacks today, police
said.
   In another incident, police discovered 300 pounds of explosives
in a car that tried to evade a police checkpoint near Belfast's
mainly Catholic Ardoyne area. The Royal Ulster Constabulary said
police believe they foiled a major bombing somewhere in the city.
   Also today, a bomb exploded just outside Belfast on the main line
to Dublin line, police said. Rail authorities said the main line
between Belfast and Lisburn was expected to be closed most of today
while security forces inspected damage. No one was injured, police
said.
   The Dublin-Belfast line has been closed 17 times this year
because of attacks by the outlawed Irish Republican Army and other
bomb alerts.
   In two sectarian attacks on Protestants in Belfast, police said
one man was shot in the stomach by men who forced their way into his
home, and two others sleeping by a bonfire were savagely beaten with
hatchets.
   In Antrim, police said, a 29-year-old Catholic man was attacked
with broken pieces of concrete and the top of some of his fingers
were hacked off.
   Police said all four victims were hospitalized in serious
condition. Three men from mainly Catholic west Belfast were arrested
in connection with the shooting attack, police said.
   In Belfast's Ardoyne area, police said they were questioning a
man after the bomb was found in a car which tried to evade a police
checkpoint. The army defused the device, which police said was
primed and ready for use.
   The IRA is fighting to end British rule in Northern Ireland and
unite the mainly Protestant province with the overwhelmingly
Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
