<FIRST>r a PM-HelicopterCrash 3rdLd-Writethru a0479 06-17 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helicopter Crash, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0479,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Dead in Army Chopper Crash on Cape Cod</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5-6th grafs pvs, `Camp Edwards...', with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with names of two victims, other detail. Picks up 7th graf pvs, `The chopper...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YARMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Guard helicopter flying in
dense fog crashed in a residential area on Cape Cod early today,
killing the six men aboard, after narrowly missing several houses,
authorities said.
   Rescue workers recovered the six bodies, using heavy equipment to
lift the UH-1 Bell helicopter and remove one of the victims pinned
underneath.
   There were no surviving crewmen and no injuries on the ground,
Fire Department Deputy William Greene said. Earlier, he had said
there were fears that more than six bodies would be found in the
wreckage.
   The helicopter was from a Delaware Army National Guard unit based
in New Castle, Del., guard spokeswoman Terry Blevins said from
Delaware. She said the regiment is attending training camp at Camp
Edwards, about 30 miles from the crash site.
   Camp Edwards is part of the Otis Air Force Base complex. A person
answering the telephone at the base this morning said the base
spokewoman was not immediately available.
   Ms. Blevins said three of the victims were from Delaware. Two of
them were identified as 1st Lt. David Joseph Hendry of Wilmington,
Del., and Staff Sgt. Benjamin Robert Greenplate, of Newark, Del. The
name of the third Delaware soldier and the other three victims were
not immediately released.
   The chopper crashed shortly after midnight in a residential
neighborhood, missing one home by just 100 feet, Greene said.
Wreckage was scattered in a 150-foot radius from the crash site.
   Police said there was no damage to homes as the helicopter cut a
20-foot-wide swath through the woods, strewing doors, glass and
other debris.
   Neighbors said the aircraft came close enough to make their
houses vibrate.
   ``We said, `This guy's going to crash,' and a couple of seconds
later he did,'' said John Palino.
   ``It was like a crumpled piece of paper,'' Palino said of the
helicopter. ``We didn't want to get near it because we were afraid
it would explode.''
   At least one resident reported hearing what sounded like engine
trouble just before the aircraft crashed. ``You could hear the
blades stopping and (then) like a thump,'' Bill O'Connor said.
   A team of military investigators reached the scene about 5:30
a.m. The cause of the crash was not immediately known, said Richard
Bunker, a state aeronautical inspector.
   Officials said one or more helicopters had been flying over
Yarmouth for much of the evening. Yarmouth is about 85 miles south
of Boston.
   ``We received several telephone calls from people in the area,''
police Sgt. Paul J. Rooney said. ``They heard a helicopter flying
low overhead and then heard the crash.''
   He said the crash was confirmed by residents about 12:10 a.m.
</TEXT>
