<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1055EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Afghanistan-Golf Bjt   06-17 0703</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Golf, Bjt,0724</SECOND>
<HEAD>Golf Balls and Rockets Soar Over Kabul Links</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-gun salute is par for the course
at the Kabul Golf and Country Club. Or, to be precise, a barrage
from the rocket launcher fired by Afghan troops in the hills near
the dusty, nine-hole course.
   ``It's great fun to play here,'' an Asian diplomat said. ``Where
else on earth do you play and pick up your own trophies?'' he added,
pointing to a pile of metal shell casings he had collected walking
from one hole to the next.
   President Najib's government, in an attempt to show that things
are getting better in battle-scarred Afghanistan, has reopened the
course and surrounding Kargha Lake area to civilians. Government
soldiers guard the golfers, mostly Asian diplomats and Asians and
Europeans working for U.N. agencies.
   The U.S.-backed guerrillas, who have been fighting since 1978 to
oust Kabul's Soviet-backed government, are only a few miles away in
the Paghman Mountains on the other side of the lake.
   Between greens, which are actually ``browns'' made of gravel, the
golfers gauge the war as well as their backswings.
   Just as they were ready to tee off Friday, their weekly day away
from work, there was a barrage of rocket fire from the government
outpost on a nearby hill.
   ``From the sound, it looks like they are using the BM-21s
today,'' the Asian diplomat said. ``Today there seems to be more
than average activity from the government side.''
   As the six golfers reached the seventh hole, there were two loud
sounds followed by billows of smoke and dust in the hills.
   ``Judging from this side's (the government's) action today, the
other side is in real trouble,'' said an Asian health official
working for the United Nations. Like the others, he asked to remain
anonymous.
   ``The fact that we are able to play golf in Kabul proves that
things are certainly getting better,'' the health official said.
``Except for the noise the missiles and rockets creates, which does
affect our game, we have no other problem.''
   But the young Afghan caddies whisper to visitors to be careful.
Sometimes new sand traps appear from week to week: bunkers dug in
the course by government soldiers.
   The 30-year-old golf course 10 miles northwest of Kabul was set
up to cater to the foreign community and once drew dozens of
golfers, mostly U.S. and Western European diplomats and U.N.
staffers. But the Americans and their allies closed their embassies
last winter, citing fears of a blood bath when the Soviet army
withdrew the last of its combat troops in February.
   So far the guerrillas have not come over the mountains to fight a
face-to-face war with the government troops, who are still supplied
by the Soviet Union. But during the winter, they stepped up their
activity around Kargha Lake, and the government declared the area
off-limits to civilians.
   ``There was a time when we used to refuse membership, but now we
want more people to join us,'' the Asian health official said.
   A decade ago, before the Soviet army arrived to back the Afghan
government in the civil war, the golf club had 45 members.
   Now only four to six golfers make the rounds on Fridays, the
weekly Islamic holy day, a non-working day for Afghans and
foreigners alike in Kabul.
   After the game, the golfers sit on the banks of a narrow stream
running beside the course. Their clubhouse has been taken over by
the Afghan army, but the golfers don't appear to mind.
   ``Here, try to put the ball in that hole,'' a West European
official from the U.N. said, handing his club to a soldier.
   The young soldier swung the club and the ball flew past the
green. His comrades laughed.
   Another stepped forward, took aim and swung. The ball came within
inches of the hole.
   ``Many of them have been watching us for months, and I am sure
some of them could be good golfers, if trained,'' the European said.
``But they have a battle to fight. But maybe one day we can have a
go with some of them.
   ``I mean in golf.''
</TEXT>
