<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1208EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Philippines-Americans     06-17 0329</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Philippines-Americans,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Warn Might Attack American Troops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist guerrillas said Saturday
that American servicemen in the Philippines are targets for attacks.
   The rebel New People's Army Central Luzon command made the
warning in a statement released to news agencies.
   Also Saturday, a newspaper reported that guerrillas had trailed
nine U.S. servicemen, apparently in preparation for an assassination
attempt.
   The rebels' policy ``of punishing American troops deployed in
U.S. military installations in the country'' is still in force, the
guerrilla statement said. It said about 1,000 Filipino soldiers
providing additional security around Clark Air Base also are targets.
   The Filipino troops were assigned to the U.S. base last year
following reports that guerrillas had trailed the nine U.S.
servicemen.
   The Pacific Stars and Stripes, an unofficial U.S. military
newspaper, quoted authorities as saying they learned of the
surveillance through documents seized in July from the New People's
Army.
   The newspaper quoted police Maj. Efren Alamares as saying the
nine _ two U.S. Air Force colonels, a lieutenant colonel, four
captains, and two sergeants _ were apparently targeted because they
lived off base.
   The U.S. military command at Clark refused comment on the rebel
statement. Capt. Donna Eggelston, a Clark spokeswoman, said the U.S.
Air Force ``periodically receives intelligence reports on terrorist
activity'' but does not comment on their content.
   Communist guerrillas have attacked Americans in the past.
   In April, guerrillas killed U.S. Army Col. James ``Nick'' Rowe as
he drove to work at the Joint U.S. Military Assistance Group in
Quezon City.
   In October 1987, rebels killed three Americans and a Filipino
civilian in coordinated ambushes outside Clark.
   The rebels have repeatedly threatened to attack U.S. personnel
because of Washington's support for President Corazon Aquino's
campaign to crush the guerrillas' 20-year insurgency.
   Some 40,000 American troops, civilians and military dependents
are stationed at six U.S. military installations in the Philippines.
More than half are stationed at Clark in central Luzon, the main
Philippine island.
</TEXT>
