<FIRST>r w AM-US-ChinaTrade     06-17 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China Trade,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investment Intended for China Could be Diverted Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thailand, the Philippines and Malaysia may
benefit from the diversion of American and other foreign investment
originally intended for the strife-torn Chinese mainland, prominent
U.S. foreign traders say.
   ``Those who have large investments in China are going to try to
continue, barring anything more cataclysmic, but it is clear and
logical that others are going to be very hesitant to make
commitments until they see if this is the beginning of the end,''
said Thomas J. White, chairman of the Asia-Pacific Council of
American Chambers of Commerce.
   Leaders of individual U.S. chambers from East Asia tended to
agree. They met reporters Friday after the annual week of meetings
in Washington between Asia-based American business executives and
members of the U.S. government and Congress.
   Thailand, the Philippines and Malaysia represent ``the next best
alternative'' to China in terms of labor costs and business
environment and because of their close association with potential
investors, White said.
   Offshore Taiwan is not an alternative for the low-cost labor
ventures attracted to the mainland, said Taiwan-based Joseph
Coffman, president of the American Chamber of Commerce in the
Republic of China.
   Even before trouble surfaced in China, many overseas Chinese
entrepreneurs had switched to Thailand, Malaysia and the Philippines
to take advantage of low labor costs, he said.
   If mainland officials ``ever get their act together, the market
potential is mind-boggling _ a market of 450 million young people
under 21,'' Coffman said. With such a market at stake, ``you can
understand the anxiety businessmen now feel.''
   For those already invested in China, ``it certainly behooves them
to try to derive something out of that investment,'' he said, but
others would be well advised to wait and see. Coffman also said
tremendous competition for foreign exchange among the different
mainland regions and cities might make it possible to make secure
investments in Chinese locations distant from Beijing.
   Bangkok-based Jerry L. Loupee, a vice chairman of the
Asia-Pacific council, said the Bush administration did the right
thing in stopping short of breaking relations with China to protest
the violent crackdown on Beijing's pro-democracy movement.
   He voiced hope that China ``will get the message'' represented by
other Asian countries drawing away some of its investment, and
create secure conditions for business to continue.
   White, who is president of Phelps Dodge Thailand, a subsidiary of
the U.S. firm, agreed. Urging that the United States coordinate
Chinese economic policy with its allies, he said, ``I hope we don't
become the only nation blocking ourselves out of the market by
taking sanctions and getting miles out in front of our competitors.''
</TEXT>
