<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1319EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-China-USStudents Bjt   06-17 0794</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-US Students, Bjt,0817</SECOND>
<HEAD>On U.S. Campuses, Many Of China's Best And Brightest Look Homeward
In Fear</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The unrest in Beijing has put the lives of tens of
thousands of Chinese students and scholars in this country in limbo,
and even the children of the elite fear they must turn away from
their homeland.
   ``If China becomes a democratic country, I will go back,'' said
Qian Songnian, a theoreticial physicist at Dartmouth College. ``But
in this situation, certainly not.''
   Chinese students began arriving in the United States in small
numbers in the years after President Nixon's visit to China. The
first large exchanges began in 1978, said Huang Zhengdong, a Yale
University law student who heads a semi-official organization of
Chinese students in the United States.
   The figure of 40,000 Chinese students now in the United States is
quoted by such groups as the Returned Student Association in
Beijing. But the U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service said a
recent computer check found 73,000 Chinese with active student visas.
   The Returned Student Association says there are an additional
40,000 Chinese students in countries other than the United States.
   The majority here are graduate students in science, engineering
and mathematics, mostly at major universities. And many are the sons
and daugters of China leaders.
   The number of student visas granted jumped from 17 in 1977 to 201
in 1978, and has soared to 18,000 new visas granted in fiscal 1988,
said spokeswoman Frances Jones of the State Department, which does
not keep cumulative figures.
   Before 1980, ``the political requirements were so tight,'' said
Huang. ``Their political backgrounds would be very clean. They came
from families that were not class enemies,'' including families who
fought for the communist revolution, workers, and peasants.
   The political restrictions were eased after 1981, he said, though
a 1987 rule said they had to show they ``love the motherland and
cherish socialism.''
   In practice, Huang said, ``People who passed the academic
examinations usually were allowed as long as their political
qualifications were not that bad.''
   California universities are the top U.S. draw, with more than
10,000 Chinese students, followed by New York, Texas, Illinois and
Massachusetts, according to the INS.
   A total of 320,000 Chinese nationals are now in the United
States, INS spokesman Greg Leo said. Following the crackdown,
Attorney General Richard Thornburgh announced that all will be
permitted to stay for at least one year.
   Though the students here are among the best and the brightest of
China, few are sponsored by their government.
   By one estimate, only 2,000 to 3,000 students receive full
government scholarships. Most graduate students are funded by their
host universities. At Stanford University, for example, not one of
the 150-odd Chinese students has a government subsidy, said Karlene
Dickey, associate dean of graduate studies.
   While official People's Republic of China media are condemning
the outbreak of ``Western bourgeois liberalism,'' it has been
fashionable for China's elite to send its sons and daughters to
study abroad where they are exposed to such ideas.
   Students and academics here said most exchange students are the
children of party members, professionals, intellectuals, teachers
and technocrats. Children and grandchildren of Politburo members are
believed to be among them.
   ``For those guys, the front door and the back door were all
open,'' said Huang.
   A University of Florida administrator added, ``I don't ever
recall coming across someone who said, `My parents are farmers.'''
Richard Downie, who has worked with Chinese students for nearly a
decade at the university's Gainesville campus, recalls one early
group who pooled their money and bought a Cadillac, which they drove
to Canada during spring break.
   ``I thought it was a great joke, because here comes a group of
people from communist China, and the first thing they buy is the
great symbol of American capitalism, the Cadillac,'' Downie said.
   Many of the students assume their government sends a few students
to keep tabs on their classmates.
   Qian, who arrived in 1981, said he believes a student in his
dormitory at the University of Maryland was an informer. When a
female classmate struck up a romance with a Taiwanese, she was
summoned to the Chinese embassy and reprimanded, he said.
   As students wrestle with whether to return home, their
government's scrutiny has taken on a more ominous tone.
   Huang said he saw someone videotaping the pro-democracy
demonstration June 5 he helped organize in New York City. He said he
was warned through intermediaries ``not to go too far,'' and his
letters have arrived opened.
   Huang, asked if he would return, only laughed.
   ``My picture and my image (are) on CNN and newspapers,'' he said.
``So certainly this is not the right time to go back.''
</TEXT>
