<FIRST>r i AM-RushdieRally     06-17 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rushdie Rally,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Rushdie Rally Turns Violent In Bradford</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Young demonstrators broke away from a
protest of the novel ``The Satanic Verses'' on Saturday and ran
through Bradford's main shopping district assaulting people and
damaging cars and shops.
   Denis O'Toole, the assistant chief constable of West Yorkshire,
said there were some arrests but no serious injuries. Two policemen
were slightly injured, he said.
   More than 200 police, some in riot gear, were deployed in an
attempt to disperse the youths, who pelted them with stones and
cans. Some youths stole soft drinks from a truck stopped at a
traffic light.
   ``A number of assaults took place as well as damage to shops and
vehicles,'' O'Toole said. He said the incident began as the
demonstration by 3,000 people outside the town hall was ending.
   Liaqat Hussain, general secretary of the Bradford Council of
Mosques, which organized the demonstration, denounced the
troublemakers.
   ``We are very sad it occurred. We were hoping for a peaceful
rally,'' he said. ``It was only a small proup of youngsters involved
in the disturbances. The majority of people were very peaceful.''
   O'Toole praised the council for its organization and attempts to
prevent any trouble.
   The controversy over ``The Satanic Verses,'' a novel by Salman
Rushdie, began in January in Bradford, the English Midlands city
with Britian's largest Moslem population.
   The book was later banned in Pakistan, India, Bangladesh,
Malaysia, Kenya, Senegal, Nigeria and other Arab nations. Riots by
people opposed to the book left 19 people dead in India and Pakistan.
   Moslems say ``The Satanic Verses'' blasphemes Islam by portraying
the wives of the Prophet Mohammed as prostitutes and insinuating
that Mohammed wrote the Koran himself rather than receiving it from
God.
   Rushdie, a British citizen who was born into a Moslem family in
India, has been in hiding since Feb. 14, when Iran's spiritual
leader Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini ordered his execution. Khomeini
died this month.
</TEXT>
