<FIRST>r a AM-SovietDissident     06-17 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Dissident,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Editor Announces Independent News Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS GINSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet dissident Sergei Grigoryants,
award-winning editor of the liberal journal Glasnost, says he has
launched an independent daily news service to carry Soviet news to
Western Europe and the United States.
   Grigoryants, on his first visit to the United States, discussed
the service Friday at a reception by the private human rights group
Freedom House, a partner in the venture. Grigoryants said he will
sign an agreement with the with the organization Monday, but that
many details have yet to be worked out.
   Daily Glasnost, an offshoot of the magazine in which Grigoryants
has tested the limits of Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
openness campaign, would be the latest in a number of Soviet
publications trying to go beyond official dispatches about Soviet
events.
   ``Recently, efforts have been made to backtrack in all spheres _
economic, and certainly, of course, in the nationalities question _
to maintain stability and to keep receiving Western credits,''
Grigoryants said in an interview.
   The nationalities question refers to the ethnic and religious
unrest that has struck several of the Soviet Union's republics in
recent months. An April 19 attack by authorities on Georgian
demonstrators left 20 dead, threatening to set back Soviet efforts
to put aside human rights as an issue in dealings with the West.
   ``There is very little time to achieve something before the
situation in the Soviet Union becomes worse,'' Grigoryants said.
``Essentially, that's what we're all doing.''
   Several unofficial publications are distributed in the West,
including Grigoryants' Glasnost and a daily digest of stories
appearing in the dissident journal Express-Khonrika.
   Glasnost has been translated and distributed in the West since
its inception two years ago. The English-language version is
translated and distributed by the New York-based Center for
Democracy.
   The Soviet government's dissemination of news worldwide is
dominated by the official news agency Tass and by broadcasts of
Radio Moscow, in addition to the main Communist Party and government
newspapers.
   Grigoryants said his editors already have begun sending Daily
Glasnost installments in Russian by telephone facsimile machines to
Paris, where they are translated into French and Spanish for
distribution to newspapers. He said the service will be expanded
with transmissions to New York for translation into English, but he
wasn't sure when.
   The plans come despite what Grigoryants, who has served several
jail terms for his activitism, called the Soviet authorities'
constant harassment of his magazine. Last week, he was given the
International Federation of Newspaper Publishers' 1989 Golden Pen of
Freedom award for his work on the magazine.
   In April 1988, agents of the KGB state security agency and the
Interior Ministry raided his suburban Moscow apartment where the
journal is published and confiscated a donated computer, files,
printing equipment, and hundreds of copies of the magazine ready for
distribution, he said. They have not been returned.
   ``They even took my English pipe,'' said the 48-year-old editor.
</TEXT>
