<FIRST>r a AM-SearsMove     06-17 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sears Move,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Illinois Offers $33 Million Package to Save Sears Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Illinois has offered $33 million to Sears, Roebuck
and Co. to keep its retail headquarters in the state it has called
home for more than 100 years.
   Sears has said it will announce by the end of the month whether
its 6,000-employee Merchandise Group will remain in Illinois or pull
up stakes. There was no Sears comment on the state's offer Friday.
   The Merchandise Group, which has a $411 million annual payroll
and produces about $19.4 million a year in state and local taxes, is
being moved from Sears Tower, the world's tallest building, which
Sears has put up for sale.
   Speculation for a new site has focused on an area west of
Chicago, Dallas, and two North Carolina cities _ Raleigh and
Charlotte.
   Sears' decision to sell Sears Tower and shift the Merchandise
Group to less costly quarters is part of a broad cost-cutting effort
announced last year by the nation's largest retailer, which is
battling inroads by discount chains and other stores.
   But the state of Illinois and city of Chicago are putting up
their own battle to keep Sears from leaving.
   Gov. James R. Thompson signed legislation Friday earmarking $33
million to the company's incentive package.
   ``This is a major retention effort for our state,'' Thompson said
in a statement. ``Sears employs 43,000 people in 857 facilities
throughout Illinois, making it the state's largest private-sector
employer.''
   Chicago already has offered unspecified incentives to Sears.
Mayor Richard M. Daley said he thinks Sears will announce a decision
by Friday.
   The state aid approved Friday could be used for land, site
improvements or infrastructure. It can be applied to any Illinois
site, and could be used for direct purchases by the state, or for
grants to Sears or local governments, said Jay Hedges, director of
the state's Department of Commerce and Community Affairs.
</TEXT>
