<FIRST>r i AM-LostLuggage     06-17 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lost Luggage,0194</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Force Jet Loses Duffle Bags, Parachute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canadian and U.S. military officials
are investigating why two duffle bags and a parachute fell from a
U.S. Air Force jet, landing on a baseball field and a nearby house.
   The incident occurred Thursday, only six weeks after a chunk of
ice fell from a commercial plane and slammed into another baseball
diamond in the same area near Winnipeg International Airport.
   That chunk of debris landed near some children.
   ``They say lightning doesn't strike in the same place twice, but
I guess in this case it did,'' airport manager George Elliot said
Friday.
   The luggage and parachute fell from one of two F-4 Phantom jets
that were leaving Winnipeg on their way to Duluth, Minn.
   The planes were from the George Air Force Base in Victorville,
Calif. and were en route home after taking part in a training
exercise in Winnipeg.
   Winnipeg National Defense spokesman Maj. Bob Butt said military
officials on both sides of the border want answers.
   ``It's always a serious matter when objects fall out of planes,''
he said.
