<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANFORD, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former astronaut Sally Ride is university
hopping, leaving Stanford to become a professor of physics at the
University of California at San Diego.
   She also will become director of the California Space Institute
at UC's Scripp's Institution of Oceanography, UC regents said Friday.
   Rider, 38, has been at Stanford for two years, examining issues
of space and nuclear weapons policy as a research fellow in the
Center for International Security and Arms Control.
   As director of the space institute, Ride will oversee research
projects on eight of the university's campuses, the regents said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mike Tyson is being sued for $200,000 by
a Florida man who claims he was struck and pushed by the heavyweight
boxing champ outside an upstate New York bar last year.
   John Copeland of Winter Haven, Fla., alleges in the lawsuit that
he sustained ``physical trauma to his arms and body, severe brusies
to his back and emotional distress.''
   The son of the bar's owner told the Albany Times Union a
different story in an account published Saturday.
   ``Mike kind of pushed the guy on the back,'' said Jacob Walthour
Jr., whose father owns the Savoias bar in Hudson, where the incident
allegedly occurred July 23, 1988. ``It was a kind of push like
you're saying, `Hi, how you doing buddy.' He (Copeland) kept saying,
`I can take your best punch. I can take your best punch.'''
   Copeland seeks compensatory damages in the lawsuit filed May 8
for negligence and punitive damages for assault and battery. Each of
the actions is for $100,000 plus interest from the date of the
incident.
   Neither Tyson's lawyers nor Copeland's would comment, the
newspaper reported.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FLINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaime Escalante, the Los Angeles high
schoolteacher who inspired the movie ``Stand and Deliver,'' played
hooky from school to accept an honorary degree.
   Escalante came to Flint on Friday to accept the degree from the
General Motors Institute, a college of engineering and business
management run by the automaker.
   ``I hate to leave my room because my students are left with a
substitute,'' Escalante said. ``It's not the same with a substitute
and it breaks the continuity of the learning process.''
   Escalante was persuaded to leave California by Fern Espino, GMI's
dean of student development. Two of Escalante's former students,
Jesus Acosta and Steve Robles, attend the institute.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kathleen Brown, another member of the
politically prominent California family, is taking a stab a
statewide office.
   Ms. Brown, whose father and brother were both governors, said
Friday she will quit her post as a local public works commissioner
next month to step up her campaign for state treasurer.
   ``One of the things that I think modern campaigns lack is the
ability to touch people and to listen to people and to find out what
it is that they see as the priorities in Sacramento,'' the
42-year-old Democrat said.
   ``It seems everywhere I go there are people there to tell me they
were touched by some positive activity of my father's or my
brother's administration,'' she said. Her father, Edmund G. ``Pat''
Brown Sr., was governor from 1959 to 1966, and her brother, Edmund
G. Jr., known as Jerry, was governor from 1975 to 1983.
   Ms. Brown, who has campaigned part-time during the past six
months for the post held by Republican incumbent Thomas W. Hayes, is
the only major Democratic candidate for the job to emerge so far.
   She was appointed to her $65,333-per-year job on the Los Angeles
Public Works Commission in October 1987 by Mayor Tom Bradley.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Columnist Art Buchwald, opera stars Robert Merrill
and Roberta Peters, and pianist Victor Borge will be featured in the
concert kicking off the 12-week season of the 104-year-old Boston
Pops.
   Celebrating its 20th anniversary on the Public Broadcast Service,
``Evening at Pops'' was taped at Boston Symphony Hall last week to
be shown June 25 here and other times in other areas.
   John Williams, who took over as Pops conductor in 1980 after the
death of Arthur Fiedler, said recently that the popularity of the
Pops seems as enduring as the orchestra itself.
   ``I don't think it's complacent to point out that the popularity
of the Pops does not seem to have diminished at all,'' he said.
   But he stressed that the orchestra must ``keep up the search for
a new repertoire, finding new things, discarding things that no
longer work.''
   ``The Pops is famous for delivering a certain glowing good
feeling that it must produce each and every time out,'' Williams
said. ``The amazing thing is that it does.''
</TEXT>
