<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Tuttle     06-17 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Tuttle,0259</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presidential Confidant Holmes Tuttle Dead at 83</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Millionaire businessman Holmes
Tuttle, a staunch Republican and confidant of presidents Reagan and
Eisenhower, has died after a brief illness. He was 83.
   Tuttle had been admitted to Cottage Hospital after suffering a
stroke eight weeks earlier, said Joseph J. Keon, his son-in-law. He
died Friday in the hospital, a nursing supervisor said.
   He was born on an Oklahoma ranch, moved to California at age 17
and made his fortune in banking and car dealerships in California
and Arizona.
   Tuttle, a one-time golfing partner of former President
Eisenhower, was a member of a group of wealthy industrialists and
friends of Ronald Reagan who helped him win the governorship of
California in 1966.
   Tuttle was a major financial supporter of state GOP politicians,
Keon said, and served with steel magnate Earle Jorgenson and
corporate executive Justin Dart as Reagan's unofficial advisers.
   He met Reagan in 1946 when he sold him a Ford coupe. At the time,
Reagan was married to Jane Wyman, who knew some of Tuttle's friends.
   Tuttle said he asked Reagan to enter the California gubernatorial
race after Reagan made speeches on behalf of Barry Goldwater in the
1964 presidential campaign.
   More recently, Tuttle and other friends of the former president
purchased a $2.5 million home in Bel Air that the Reagans moved into
after leaving the White House.
   He is survived by his wife, Virginia; a son, Robert Tuttle; and a
daughter, Sally Keon.
</TEXT>
