<DOCNO> AP890617-0085 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1503EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Dukakis-IllegalAliens     06-17 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dukakis-Illegal Aliens,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dukakis Proposes Deportation for Illegal Immigrants in Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Michael Dukakis has proposed deporting the
illegal aliens now in Massachusetts prisons as a measure to relieve
overcrowding while saving money.
   ``If we can deport them, we're going to deport them,'' Dukakis
said Friday. ``I don't see any reason why the people of this state
ought to be supporting folks who are here illegally in the first
place.''
   State Secretary of Human Services Philip Johnston, who oversees
the state corrections system, said, ``We want to try to deport as
many of these people as possible. We'll even pay their airfare.''
   State prisons and county jails are overflowing with nearly 13,000
inmates in facilities designed to hold 7,100. Inmates are doubling
and even tripling up in cells and are even sleeping in hallways,
boiler rooms and recreation rooms.
   INS Boston district director Charles Cobb welcomed Dukakis'
interest in deporting illegal aliens and said the U.S. government
can pay their outbound plane fare. ``We have money to move people,''
Cobb said.
   In the past, the INS waited for jailed illegal immigrants to
complete their sentences before starting the deportation process.
But in January, they stopped waiting and now proceed with the hope
that inmates can be deported when they get out of prison.
   Immigrants comprise 10 percent of the state's criminal inmate
population, and as many as 80 percent of them could be deported for
being in this country illegally, according to estimates from the
federal Immigration and Naturalization Service.
   ``The governor and I both view this as a top priority,'' Johnston
said. ``We want to move quickly to work with INS to deport as many
people as possible, consistent with public safety.''
   He also noted the potential cost saving. The state spends about
$30,000 to house each inmate; creating a new prison bed costs
$100,000.
   If illegal aliens are deported, Johnston said, ``we can save
ourselves two or three New Braintrees,'' referring to the
controversial 500-bed prison planned for that town.
</TEXT>
