<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND MOUND, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Beware: Guard Duck on Duty,'' reads a
sign at the Minnehaha Grocery Store gasoline pumps.
   Minnie, named after the store, happened along on June 6, strutted
back and forth near the pumps for a while, then took up her post
between two pumps. She's been there almost every day since.
   At first, store employees didn't feed the muscovy duck because
they wanted her to stay independent. They'd take her to a nearby
pond, hoping she'd make her home there, but she insisted on flying
or walking back.
   A few days ago, a customer with two bird dogs in the back of his
truck drove up, and Minnie fled into the highway. She ducked beneath
a passing car, suffered only an injured leg and is pack at her post.
   Store owner Mel Hjelm was perplexed by the duck's affinity for
the store, but his friend Cindy Lynberg has a theory.
   ``I think she sees herself in her reflection in the gas pumps,''
Lynberg said. ``I think she thinks it's another duck.
   ``I think she's in love with herself.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DARIEN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You might think that Carolyn Lambiasi is a
fearsome 5-year-old now that she has a black belt in tae kwon do.
   You might wonder how her mother handles a little girl who knows
how to do jump sidekicks, who has three big first-place trophies at
her home in this Chicago suburb for competing in the under-16
category.
   The answer is that tae kwon do is more than a kick-punch-block
self-defense sport, according to her instructor.
   ``It's a philosophy to respect persons. It's a discipline,''
Chung Kim, 32, said.
   Kim says he won't accept students who don't willingly help with
household chores, abide by parents' decisions and diligently pursue
their studies.
   In any case, there's no need to worry that Carolyn will run
roughshod over her two older brothers, Christopher, 11, and Carlton,
7, and her sister Christina, 8. All four are students of Kim, as is
their mother, Celia, a nurse.
