<FIRST>r i AM-Harrods     06-17 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Harrods,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harrods' New Dress Code Makes Short-Shorts a No No</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Mohamed cq in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Harrods made it official Saturday. Even when it's
hot outside, skimpily dressed shoppers are not welcome at the
elegant emporium.
   Britain's best-known department store defended its new ``cover up
or keep out'' order, saying shoppers should not dress like
beachgoers.
   ``When you come shopping at the best store in the world, you
should be wearing something suitable, not something more appropriate
to the beach,'' said a Harrods spokesman, speaking anonymously.
   As temperatures soared to an unseasonably hot 81 degrees,
customers wearing revealing outfits were being shown the door on the
instructions of Mohamed Al Fayed, chairman of House of Fraser, which
owns the Knightsbridge store.
   ``In the kind of temperatures we have been experiencing lately,
people have been going just too far in their skimpy shorts and
T-shirts,'' the spokesman said. ``We have always had a dress code,
but we now feel the need to redefine it. Mr. Al Fayed has made a
personal decision on this and requests customers to wear suitable
attire for the store.''
   People wearing short-shorts, tops that reveal too much, and
cut-off, tatty jeans will be kept out, the spokesman said, but
tailored or Bermuda shorts are fine _ ``very fashionable this summer
and which we sell in the store anyway.''
   Staff at all 11 entrances to Harrods are under orders to inspect
the clothing of every shopper.
   ``If a customer fails to come up to scratch, he or she would
politely but firmly be denied entry,'' the spokesman said.
   The spokesman said some customers were ``not terribly happy when
turned away, but in the main everyone has accepted the situation.''
   Music teacher John Locke, 29, was quoted in the tabloid Today as
saying he was barred from the store by a doorman. ``I was told I was
wearing football (soccer) shorts. It's an infantile policy,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
