<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1538EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BishopsConference     06-17 0633</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bishops Conference,0650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bishops Seek Greater Role For Black Catholics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRIGGS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SOUTH ORANGE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Led by a black nun with cancer, the
nation's Roman Catholic bishops Saturday linked arms and sang ``We
Shall Overcome'' before agreeing to seek ways to give blacks a
greater role in the church.
   The National Conference of Catholic Bishops also passed a
resolution urging normalization of U.S. relations with Vietnam and
approved a plan for resolving disputes between bishops and
theologians.
   Tears streamed down the faces of some bishops as they listened to
Sister Thea Bowman of Canton, Miss., who pleaded for the church to
be more sensitive to the needs of black Catholics.
   The number of black Catholics in the United States has grown from
900,000 to 2 million in the past 20 years, partly helped by
immigration from Haiti and the West Indies. There are 53 million
American Catholics.
   Only 13 of the church's 300 bishops are black. In addition, there
are 1,100 predominantly black parishes in the nation, but only 75 of
the approximately 300 black priests are pastors of black churches.
   Sister Bowman, who works at the Institute of Black Studies at
Xavier University in New Orleans, said too many white priests ``work
for the people, but have not learned to share life and love. They
insulate themselves because they don't feel comfortable with black
people.''
   The bishops conference voted to refer a proposed document from
the Bishops' Committee on Black Catholics to its Administrative
Board. The document urges greater representation of blacks
throughout the church and integration of African-American cultural
symbols into local parishes and liturgies.
   In the document titled ``Here I Am, Send Me,'' the nation's 13
black prelates say the nation and church are still burdened with
racism, and there has been a serious attrition of blacks from the
church to Protestant denominations ``where they feel more at home.''
   Auxiliary Bishop Moses B. Anderson of Detroit, a black prelate,
said it is good for Catholics to hear church leaders discuss ways to
celebrate black culture.
   Auxiliary Bishop John H. Ricard of Baltimore, chairman of the
black Catholics committee, said the finished document likely will be
brought before the bishops at their November meeting.
   On the Vietnam issue, the bishops approved a statement asking the
nation to begin to heal the wounds caused by the Vietnam War and
resume diplomatic relations with its former enemy.
   ``The United States government ... must move beyond hostility and
adopt a traditional American response to the needs of desperate and
hungry people,'' the bishops said.
   The committee, which visited Vietnam in January, said the call to
normalize relations does not indicate approval of the communist
regime, but could serve as a means to provide humanitarian
assistance and more effectively lobby for improvements in human
rights and religious liberty for the Vietnamese.
   Bishop Joseph J. Madera of Fresno, Calif., who said the brother
of a priest in his diocese is one of 10 imprisoned priests in
Vietnam, expressed concerns that the church would be granting
legitimacy to a ``barbaric'' regime.
   In other business, the bishops voted 214-9 to approve a document
on ``Doctrinal Responsibilities'' recommending ways for bishops and
theologians to resolve disputes through dialogues.
   The document, first presented before the bishops' conference in
November 1987, drew initial criticism for appearing to place bishops
and theologians on an equal level.
   But much of the criticism was deflected after the document was
changed to emphasize the bishops' role as the final arbiter of
doctrinal disputes.
   ``It's primarily a call to civility and charity. I don't feel
bound by it in any way,'' said Cardinal John O'Connor on New York.
   The bishops planned to attend Mass together Sunday and meet in
executive session at the end of their four-day meeting Monday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
