<DOCNO> AP890617-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1540EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseGOP-Michel 1stLd-Writethru a0522 06-17 0972</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House GOP-Michel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0522,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Genial Republican Leader Having To Learn More Militant Tactics</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 10th graf, ``What he xxx and 15th graf, ``It was xxx to
provide ^additioanl identification for Bonior and Coelho</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Republican Leader Robert Michel keeps a
videotape in his office of the House proceedings on Oct. 29, 1987,
the day Speaker Jim Wright stretched the rules to snatch a rare
legislative victory from the GOP.
   Once in a while, it is brought out and replayed as a reminder of
the indignities House Republicans suffer as their 35-year minority
status continues. It is a condition that has never been as wearisome
as during Wright's tenure these past 2{ years, and Michel _ by
personality a quiet, gentlemanly legislator _ has been forced to
learn some new tactics.
   The transformation was most noticeably on display the day Wright
stepped down as speaker. Addressing the House on an occasion that
seemed made for conciliation and courtesy, Michel instead turned
critical.
   ``The distinguished members of the committee on ethics ... are
neither mindless nor cannibals,'' he said in rebuttal to Wright's
resignation speech a week before.
   ``I am all for putting an end to bitterness. I am all in favor of
putting our house in order. But we do not do so by sweeping things
under the rug.''
   He also observed that ``thirty-five years of uninterrupted power
can act like a corrosive acid upon the restraints of civility and
comity. Those who have been kings of the hill for so long may forget
that majority status is not a divine right.''
   Michel's more partisan demeanor has prompted criticism from
Democrats and the attention of Republicans.
   ``It's there, and there isn't any room to argue about whether Bob
is more partisan,'' says Rep. Edward Madigan, a fellow Illinois
Republican who shares Michel's preference for reasoned discourse
over confrontation.
   While Michel said later he was simply stating ``what had to be
said,'' his remarks angered many Democrats, who saw it as kicking
Wright while he was down.
   ``What he said was beneath him,'' said Rep. David Bonior of
Michigan, No. 4 in the House Democratic leadership hierarchy. ``I
think he knows deep down it was inappropriate.''
   Michel's approach to leading his Republican cadre also has
changed for another reason: changes in the makeup of the 175-member
GOP conference itself. An influx of younger members elected since
1982 has brought a growing disaffection with compromise and a
proclivity for more rhetorical bomb-throwing.
   Many Democrats believe Michel's occasional forays into hardball
politics are a reflection of that newer group, epitomized by Rep.
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., the man who contributed mightily to bringing
down Wright and who was elected the party's No. 2 leader this year.
   Michel's comments when he handed the House gavel over to new
Speaker Tom Foley ``fits right in with the markup of Gingrich's
attacks,'' Bonior said. ``It meshes comfortably with the rhetoric of
the far Republican right.''
   ``It was indicative of the embattled Bob Michel as opposed to the
one of the past, who was consensus building,'' said Rep. Tony Coelho
of California, who was No. 3 in the Democratic leadership before
giving up his House seat because of questions about a junk bond
deal. ``It was a Bob Michel who was looking behind his back. ... The
division that exists on their side is quite severe, and he senses
it, feels it and reacts to it all the time.''
   Whether things will change with the ascension of Foley remains to
be seen.
   ``I wouldn't want to predict that,'' Michel said. ``It gives us
an opportunity for a fresh start, and I'm going to try and make the
most of it.''
   Bonior was less sanguine. ``This kind of internecine warfare
could continue to go on for the rest of this Congress,'' he said.
   ``The leader has to more or less reflect the spirit, the
attitudes, the values of his troops,'' said Republican Rep. Henry
Hyde, another Illinoisan. ``We saw Jim Wright move to the left as he
ascended the ladder of leadership. Tom Foley has done the same. And
the Republicans have become more militant in the past four years
because of abuses of power by the Democrats.''
   Foley, in an interview last week after his election to the
speakership, acknowledged _ without naming Wright _ that Democrats
had at times overplayed their majority privileges.
   He singled out the 1987 vote on a budget bill, when Wright
created two legislative days out of one and held open a roll-call
long enough for one Democrat to change his vote and provide the
winning margin. ``I think we went too far on that day,'' he said,
and promised an end to such overreaching.
   The deterioration of House comity dates to 1985, when Democrats
denied a House seat to Republican Richard McIntyre of Indiana in a
disputed close election. The 1987 budget vote added fuel to the
fire, as did later clashes over aid to the Nicaraguan contras and
Wright's alleged disclosure of a CIA covert operation in Nicaragua.
   In the latter case, Michel shocked some Republicans by joining
Rep. Dick Cheney, R-Wyo., in filing a formal ethics complaint
against Wright.
   On Contra aid, Michel felt he had been cheated out of the right
in March 1988 to a vote on a GOP alternative. ``We were promised a
fair shot at a substitute. We got a shot all right, a shot in the
head,'' he said. In a statement, he later added: ``In over 30 years
as a member of this institution, I have kept my word. I expect
others to do the same.''
   ``If Wright had treated Republicans more evenhandedly, like
(former speakers) Carl Albert or Tip O'Neill, you would not see this
significant change in Bob Michel's behavior,'' Madigan said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
