<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-US-China     06-17 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>California Senator Urges Trade Sanction Against China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Pete Wilson said Saturday that maintaining
business-as-usual with China's repressive regime is ``intolerable''
and called for revocation of that country's favored trading status
with the United States.
   ``The United States must be a moral leader,'' the California
Republican said in an appearance on CNN's ``Newsmaker Saturday.
``... I think we've got to do that with some concrete, tangible
means.''
   He expressed dismay at President Bush's reluctance to go beyond a
cutoff of military sales in protesting the Beijing government's
crackdown on pro-democracy students and other dissidents.
   Wilson said he will offer a nonbinding resolution on Monday
calling for revocation of China's most-favored-nation trading status.
   Trading partners with that status are guaranteed trade relations
with the United States that are as favorable as any those of any
other nation.
   Although such a resolution is non-binding, Wilson said it is
important to put Congress on record against the Chinese regime's
bloody repression of the pro-democracy movement, its massacre of
peaceful demonstrators near Tiananmen Square and its continued
campaign to arrest and denounce the dissidents.
   ``The United States is the largest direct investor in the
People's Republic of China,'' Wilson said. ``The hope is ... that a
more moderate leadership takes over, but one can assist that to come
about.''
   He said the United States brought trade pressures against the
Soviet Union to press for human rights reforms and should do so with
China.
   Wilson complained about reports that business representatives,
particularly from Japan, are returning to China in spite of the
crackdown.
   ``Business as usual _ it's intolerable,'' Wilson said. ``It ought
to be condemned.''
   But a former ambassador to China, Winston Lord, echoed Bush in
saying that trade trade sanctions often ``hurt the people'' instead
of the government.
   Calling the question one over which ``reasonable people can
disagree,'' Lord said on the same program that it would not be in
America's best interest ``to dismantle accords, legislation and
blueprints (of an economic relationship) that have taken years to
build.''
   Lord argued that ultimately, the aged Chinese leaders now in
charge of the repression will pass away and the United States will
want to maintain its economic and trade ties for that moment.
   The former ambassador, who was in China in February when Bush
visited Beijing, applauded the president's approach and said the
administration's ``rhetoric should continue to be strong.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
