<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     06-17 0289</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0299</SECOND>
<HEAD>Syrian Gunners Fire into Christian Ports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian gunners fired 150 howitzer shells
into the three main ports north of Beirut on Saturday and clashed
with Christian forces along Beirut's dividing Green Line. Police
said one civilian died.
   There were no casualties in the barrage on the Jounieh, Tabarja
and Byblos ports through which food, fuel and occasionally weapons
are smuggled into the 310-square-mile Christian enclave, police said.
   In Christian East Beirut, a man was killed by sniper fire, they
said.
   That brought the toll to 373 people killed and 1,450 wounded
since clashes broke out March 8 between Gen. Michel Aoun's mainly
Christian troops and the allied Syrian and Lebanese Druse forces.
   Last week, Syrian gunners attacked an oil tanker and three boats
carrying food and gasoline to the Christian enclave. In response,
Aoun said Friday he would attack the network of roads along which
the Syrians bring in supplies from Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   Aoun did not say how he would carry out attacks on the roads,
which would be a dramatic escalation of the 3-month-old
confrontation.
   Meanwhile, newspapers in Lebanon on Saturday warned of an
escalation in fighting, which began when Aoun blockaded illegal
militia-run ports that he said deprived the state treasury of $100
million yearly. The Syrians responded by blockading the Christian
enclave.
   ``If the trends of escalation and tension persist in Lebanon,
they would lead to a renewed outbreak of war at a large scale,'' the
daily An-Nahar quoted an unidentified U.S. diplomatic source as
saying.
   Syrian troops entered Lebanon under a 1976 Arab League
peacekeeping mandate one year after the countri's civil war began.
They later sided with the Moslems.
</TEXT>
