<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     06-17 0327</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showers and Thunderstorms Linger in the East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms and showers that fell Saturday across the
Southeast, and storms in the Midwest grew stronger.
   Eastern Virginia, the Carolinas, central and southern Georgia and
the Florida panhandle got rain Saturday, the day after strong storms
moved through much of the eastern part of the nation.
   Intensifying thunderstorms in the Midwest brought showers from
North Dakota and South Dakota into western Minnesota, Nebraska,
eastern Kansas, western Missouri and north-central Oklahoma.
   Thunderstorms also were scattered over Lower Michigan, northern
Indiana, northern Ohio and western New York.
   Rain extended along the northern Pacific coast.
   Heavier rainfall during the 6 hours up to 2 p.m. EDT included 2
inches at Panama City, Fla., almost an inch at Myrtle Beach, S.C.,
three-quarters of an inch at Jacksonville, N.C., and two-thirds of
an inch at Wilmington, N.C.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 54
degrees at Traverse City, Mich., to 107 degrees at Phoenix. The
nation's low temperature Saturday morning was 31 degrees at
Yellowstone, Wyo.
   The national weather forecast for Sunday was for showers and
thunderstorms from southern Wisconsin across Illinois, eastern
Missouri, Kentucky, Indiana, southwest Lower Michigan, Ohio and West
Virginia. Scattered showers were predicted for northern and central
New England and northeastern New York state.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s in much of New
England, inland New York state, Pennsylvania, Ohio, the Great Lakes,
Indiana, Wisconsin, eastern Iowa, Minnesota, from central Montana
across the northern Pacific Coast and scattered along the California
coast. Highs should be in the 90s in much of Florida, and to near
100 degrees in Texas, New Mexico and the Great Basin of Nevada and
western Utah. Highs in the 90s to near 115 degrees were expected in
inland valleys of central California and through the desert
Southwest. High temperatures in the remainder of the nation
generally were expected to be in the 80s.
</TEXT>
