<DOCNO> AP890617-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1721EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SmokeJumpers     06-17 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Smoke Jumpers,0265</SECOND>
<HEAD>Smoke Jumpers Gather for Reunion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOISE, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smoke jumpers from across the country dropped
in for the weekend in Boise to mark their occupation's 50th
anniversary.
   ``For a lot of us, it's still in our blood,'' said reunion
organizer and former smoke jumper Les Tschohl. He estimated that
1,000 current and former smoke jumpers would attend the reunion,
which started Friday.
   There are only 400 active smoke jumpers in the nation, Tschohl
said. All must first be firefighters and go through an intensive
four weeks of training before they are used to fight forest fires.
   Once on the ground, their main tool is a shovel. A typical smoke
jumper's fire is a single tree ablaze. Last year, they stopped
hundreds of lightning strikes from becoming infernos in the
backcountry.
   ``Smoke jumpers are designed for rapid initial attack,'' Tschohl
said.
   Earl Cooley, 77, who made the first jump into a forest fire on
July 12, 1940, the summer after the smoke jumping technique was
developed, said parachuting never scared him. Even so, he said, ``It
just isn't natural to stick your head out the door and jump into
open space.''
   Mark Klinger, a current smoke jumped, said advances in the
quality of parachutes have made the job safer and easier.
   Tschohl said, however, that smoke jumpers are tradition-bound,
and still sew their own jumping clothes and parachutes.
   ``I got pretty good on the sewing machine after a while,''
Tschohl said, adding that he knows one smoke jumper who makes
dresses for his wife.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
