<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1722EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Iran-Crime 1stLd-Writethru a0508 06-17 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Crime, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0508,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Convicted Saboteurs, 15 Drug Traffickers Hanged</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with 15 more hangings and changes throughout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran hanged two would-be saboteurs and 15
drug traffickers Saturday, and officials arrested 11 other suspected
drug smugglers in the past week, Tehran television reported.
   The 17 executions were the first reported since the country's
spiritual leader, Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, died June 3.
   The television broadcast, monitored in Cyprus, said the 15 drug
traffickers were convicted of smuggling and distributing more than
880 pounds of illegal narcotics. It said they were sentenced by
Islamic courts and hanged in western Bakhtaran province.
   It reported the two men convicted of attempted sabotage were
executed in Zahedan, the capital of southeastern Sistan-Baluchestan
province, and identified them as Piri Qanbarzehi and Abdolghani
Rakhshani. The report did not give their ages or further information
about them.
   It said both were charged with the illegal possession of weapons
and explosives and of ``plotting against national security.''
   The broadcast did not mention any act of sabotage.
   In another report from Zahedan the television report said 11
suspected drug smuggler were arrested and 1,851 pounds of narcotics
confiscated in three raids. It said police seized 66 pounds of
heroin and t1,785 pounds of opium.
   A law that went into effect last January mandates the death
penalty for anyone found in the possession of even small quantities
of drugs. Hundreds have since been executed for drug offenses.
   Most traffickers have been arrested in Sistan-Baluchestan or
northeastern Khorasan province on the borders with Pakistan and
Afghanistan.
   The U.S. State Department and some humanitarian organizations,
including London-based Amnesty International, have criticized Iran
for a large number of executions.
   Reports have said many of those executed were political prisoners
opposed to Iran's fundamentalist Islamic rule.
</TEXT>
