<FIRST>r a AM-MobsterSlaying     06-17 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mobster Slaying,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Confirm Reputed Crime Boss A Homicide Victim</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The positive identification Saturday of
the body of a reputed New England mob boss has alerted federal
authorities to the possibility of an underworld power struggle.
   The death of William P. Grasso, 62, was ruled a homicide after an
autopsy showed that the New Haven man died of a single gunshot wound
to the neck, authorities said.
   Two fishermen found Grasso's body Friday in woods along the shore
of the Connecticut River in Wethersfield, just south of Hartford.
The body was partly submerged.
   It was unclear when the shooting occurred, how long the body had
been lying by the river or how it got there, said Sgt. Scott O'Mara
of the state police.
   Grasso was identified by the FBI last year as a top-ranking
member of the Patriarca crime family, based in Providence, R.I.,
which is said to control illegal gambling, loan-sharking and other
rackets in Hartford, New Haven, Boston, Providence, Worcester,
Mass., and many smaller cities and towns in an area stretching from
Connecticut to Maine.
   Grasso was the ``single most influential organized crime figure
in Connecticut,'' and ``one of the top two if not the top in New
England,'' said U.S. Attorney Stanley A. Twardy.
   ``It's a very nasty business Mr. Grasso allegedly was in.
Usually, we have to sit back and see what something like this shakes
loose,'' said Assistant U.S. Attorney John Durham, who heads the
Organized Crime Strike Force in Connecticut.
   Twardy said the primary concern of federal agents is to determine
``what led to this murder'' and whether it was an ``internally
sanctioned hit or an unsanctioned hit.
   ``If this is an internally sanctioned hit involving the Patriarca
family, then that would probably be the end of it,'' Twardy said.
``But if it is an unsanctioned hit, a feud between families, there
promise to be further hits down the road.''
   The U.S. attorney said the FBI is investigating whether there is
a connection between Grasso's death and the wounding Friday outside
Boston of another reputed Patriarca leader. Francis P. Salemme, 56,
was the target of an attack by four men firing assault rifles,
authorities said.
   According to published reports in Boston and Providence, which
quoted unidentified law officers, Salemme was an heir-apparent in
the Patriarca family.
   The Boston Globe on Saturday quoted unnamed sources as saying
Grasso's death could signal a war between the Patriarca family and
the New York-based Genovese crime family. The sources said Grasso
had been expected for some time to make a power grab in Springfield,
Mass., territory now controlled by the Genovese family.
   Known for keeping an extremely low profile, Grasso gained
underworld prominence in 1984 upon the death of Raymond L.
Patriarca, who had run his organization from a vending machine
company office in Providence for 25 years. Grasso assumed a
high-echelon position under Ray Patriarca Jr., Providence police
were quoted as saying at the time.
   Federal officials said that in recent years the younger Patriarca
has seemed more interested in developing land in northern Rhode
Island than in the business of the crime family.
   The Providence-Journal on Saturday quoted an unidentified law
enforcement source as saying the shootings may indicate that someone
in New England is displeased with Patriarca's low-key leadership.
   In the late 1970s, Grasso was the target of state and federal
investigations, including a grand jury probe of allegations he
controlled illegal gambling in New Haven. The investigations never
led to his arrest.
   More recently, investigators had focused on Grasso because of the
disappearance in March 1988 of an East Hartford restaurateur who
allegedly had run afoul of the New York mob, and the slaying in
December 1988 of Eric Miller, a professional boxer from Hartford,
according to published reports.
</TEXT>
