<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--China-Poll     06-17 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--China-Poll,0181</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Opinion Of China Plummets, Poll Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American opinion of China soured dramatically
after the regime's bloody crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators,
but Americans strongly support President Bush's restrained response,
a poll concludes.
   Seventy-eight percent of Americans surveyed had an unfavorable
opinion of China, a reversal from March when 72 percent of
respondents had a favorable opinion, according to a Los Angeles
Times poll published in early Sunday editions.
   Of the 1,417 adults surveyed nationwide, 12 percent considered
China a safe place for Americans to invest money, and only 9 percent
regard the country as a safe place for American tourists.
   But Americans supported Bush's response to the massacre in
Tiananmen Square and the hardline leadership's suppression of the
pro-democracy movement, according to the poll.
   Three-fourths of those surveyed approved of Bush's decision to
halt U.S. military sales to China and to suspend visits between the
nation's military leaders, the poll shows.
   The telephone poll, conducted Wednesday and Thursday, had a
margin of error of three percentage points either way.
</TEXT>
