<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Queen     06-17 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Queen,0432</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guards Troop Color for Queen's Official Birthday</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos LON2,6</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of soldiers in scarlet tunics and bearskin
hats trooped in precise formation before Queen Elizabeth II on
Saturday for her official birthday celebration.
   The royal family was out in strength for the Trooping the Color
ceremony. The queen mother turned 63 on April 21, but the official
celebration is set on a day in June because the weather is likely to
be better.
   Spectators lined the way as horse-drawn carriages bearing the
queen and family members made their way slowly down the broad Mall
that leads from Buckingham Palace toward the the graveled open space
of the Horse Guards Parade for the big event.
   To the cadence of military bands, rank after rank of footsoldiers
marched along the avenue and hundreds of cavalrymen in plumed
helmets and chrome-plated breastplates rode by on gleaming horses,
spurs jangling and swords glinting in the sun.
   One coach carried the Queen Mother Elizabeth, the Princess of
Wales and her two sons, Prince William, nearly 7, who is second in
line to the throne after his father Prince Charles, and Prince
Harry, who will be 5 in September.
   It was Harry's first year in the parade and although he is no
stranger to royal pomp, he seemed just as awed by it all as the
spectators. While William waved he sat quite still watching the
cheering crowds
   Charles and his father, Prince Philip, rode horseback, as did the
queen's cousin the Duke of Kent _ all in the scarlet uniforms of the
prestigious Guards regiments that participate in the annual ceremony.
   The queen, wearing a blue and white silk dress and wide-brimmed
hat, stood on a dais at the parade ground as the 1st Battalion
Coldstream Guards trooped the color, or regimental flags, past.
   After the ceremony the queen rode back along the Mall to
Buckingham Palace, where she and members of the family made an
appearance on the balcony to watch a Royal Air Force fly-past by 11
planes, including jet fighters of the aerobatics team called the Red
Arrows.
   Harry finally waved at the crowd, smiling broadly.
   The Trooping has been a regular event since the turn of the
century, but during the 18th and 19th centuries it was an erratic
occasion, seldom, if ever, attended by the monarch.
   In 1845, Queen Victoria wrote that she drove in a ``small green
chariot,'' ``quite incog'' and had ``an admirable view of the parade
without being found out.''
</TEXT>
