<FIRST>u i AM-UN-Cambodia     06-17 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Cambodia,0546</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Plan Would Send Thousands of Peacekeepers to Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Spotlight-Cambodia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of military observers would
supervise a Cambodian peace agreement under a U.N. plan that parties
to the 11-year-old war are discussing, according to a senior
diplomat.
   He said it would be one of the most expensive peacekeeping
operations undertaken by the United Nations.
   Vietnam has announced it will withdraw all of its 70,000
remaining troops from Cambodia by Sept. 30 and the diplomat said
Friday the United Nations is running short of time to formulate a
peace plan.
   There have been negotiations between the Vietnamese-installed
government of Premier Hun Sen and a fractious alliance of three
opposition groups _ the radical Khmer Rouge, non-communist forces
loyal to former Premier Son Sann and supporters of ex-head of state
Prince Norodom Sihanouk.
   The opposition groups have been fighting a guerrilla war against
the government since Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978,
ousted the Khmer Rouge and set up another communist government.
   The Khmer Rouge gained power in the spring of 1975, defeating the
U.S.-backed government. More than a million people were killed in
purges by the Khmer Rouge and its forced evacuation of the cities to
abolish all Western influence.
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar, in a speech last month
to the Asia Society, said U.N. officials have prepared a provisional
plan for ending the conflict and organizing a government of national
reconciliation. He said the plan has been circulated among the
warring parties, but he provided no details.
   The senior diplomat, who represents one of the nations involved
in the Cambodian entanglement, said the U.N. plan under
consideration calls for at least 2,000 U.N. military observers plus
election observers to oversee balloting for a coalition government.
The diplomat spoke with the condition he not be identified.
   He emphasized the plan is in the preliminary stage and said an
international conference to be held in Paris in August will decide
what nations would be acceptable as U.N. peacekeepers.
   Negotiations are set for July 24-25 in Paris between Hun Sen's
government and the opposition alliance.
   The diplomat said the Cambodian groups have to determine the
status of the armed resistance forces. The Khmer Rouse is the
strongest and best organized, with an estimated 30,000 combat
veterans. Sihanounk, Son Sann and Hun Sen have declared their
opposition to participation by Khmer Rouge leaders responsible for
the mass killings in the late 1970s.
   Vietnam has resisted U.N. involvement because the world body
still recognizes the regime ousted by the Vietnamese as Cambodia's
legitimate government.
   Vietnam and Cambodia have expressed a preference for India,
Poland and Canada to supervise the Vietnamese troop withdrawal.
   But the senior diplomast said he believed the United Nations
would supervise the withdrawal and the establishment of some form of
coalition government.
   He said that of the five permanent members of the U.N. Security
Council the United States, Britain, France and China oppose the
Vietnamese-installed government and favor a strong U.N. role.
   The Soviet Union, the fifth permanent member and Vietnam's main
backer, probably would accept a U.N. peacekeeping operation and
influence Vietnam to cooperate, the diplomat said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
