<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1833EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RockyFlats     06-17 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rocky Flats,0309</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bonuses To Rockwell Frozen Because Of Rocky Flats Investigation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Energy has frozen nearly $5
million in bonus payments to the operator of the Rocky Flats nuclear
weapons plant, which is under investigation for alleged
environmental crimes.
   The bonuses were to be paid to Rockwell International Corp. for
its management of the plant, which manufactures plutonium triggers
for nuclear bombs. The payments were to cover work performed between
September 1988 and March 1989.
   The bonuses have been ``frozen indefinitely,'' said W. Henson
Moore, Energy Department Deputy Director.
   Scores of FBI agents and Environmental Protection Agency
investigators raided the plant June 6 looking for evidence of
illegal dumping and incineration of hazardous wastes. The
investigation is continuing.
   ``They're not going to get that money until we know more,'' about
the alleged misdeeds, Moore said Friday.
   Ed Heintz, Rocky Flats spokesman for Rockwell, learned of the
bonus freeze Friday night from a Denver Post reporter, the newspaper
said.
   ``I'm just amazed,'' Heintz said. ``As far as we can tell,
Rockwell is not aware of that action.''
   The DOE has warned Rockwell that any violations of environmental
laws at the plant will be considered a breach of its five-year, $2.5
billion contract.
   In a June 15 letter to Rockwell Chairman Donald Beall, Energy
Secretary James Watkins said that if ``any instances of intentional
(waste) discharges either in excess of, or not sanctioned by,
applicable environmental permits or compliance agreements were to
occur, we should both consider that wholly inconsistent with the
obligations placed on Rockwell by its contract,'' Watkins wrote.
   Watkins gave Rockwell 60 days to present him with a
``comprehensive plan that will indicate ... how Rockwell will
provide a satisfactory level of assurance that management
shortcomings ... will not occur.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
