<HEAD>Humanitarian Group Cancels Aid Offer to China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The organization Medecins sans Frontiers (Doctors
without Borders) called off its effort help people injured in
clashes in China between troops and pro-democracy demonstrators.
   The group said in a statement Friday night that it was unable to
ensure that its doctors could oversee the use of more than 17 tons
of supplies sent to Beijing ``and does not envisage, in the current
context, cooperation with the authorities.''
   It said the medicines and surgical equipment will be shipped to
other Asian countries where Medecins sans Frontiers teams are
working.
   The statement said those who donated funds specifically for use
in China could get their money back if they asked. The organization
began its ``Plane of Life'' program 10 days ago, appealing for help
for ``the victims of repression in China.''
   A chartered plane with 24 tons of supplies went to Hong Kong and
more than 17 tons was flown to Beijing.
