<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 1941EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Time     06-17 0575</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Takes Case for Warner Deal to Shareholders, Puts Off Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. is asking shareholders to reject an
unwanted $10.7 billion takeover bid from Paramount Communications
Corp. and approve its decision to make an offer for its would-be
merger partner, Warner Communications Inc.
   In a letter to shareholders released Saturday, Time reiterated
the stand it took Friday. The media giant announced then it had
turned down the Paramount bid and amended the terms of its earlier
stock-swap merger agreement with Warner to include a $14 billion
tender offer for Warner at $70 a share.
   Time also said its shareholders meeting scheduled for Friday _ at
which stockholders were expected to vote on the original Time-Warner
merger proposal _would be adjourned until June 30.
   At that time, shareholders are expected to vote on the election
of directors and other business, but no matters related to the
proposed merger with Warner, Time said.
   Time told shareholders the early returns of proxies mailed in
connection with the earlier merger agreement strongly supported the
Time-Warner combination. However, many of these proxies likely were
received before Paramount announced its $175-per-share cash bid on
June 6.
   Time told shareholders Paramount's offer was ``highly conditional
and subject to many uncertainties, including obtaining the necessary
$14 billion of financing and all required regulatory approvals.''
   Time repeated its estimate that it would take as long as a year
for Paramount to win the approvals required from some 800 cable
television systems for which Time now holds franchises. That would
delay the completion of Paramount's bid and, consequently, payments
to Time shareholders for their stock.
   In the letter and an accompanying Securities and Exchange
Commission filing, Time also charged that terms of the financing for
Paramount's offer have not been determined or negotiated.
   Time officials made each of these points in statements and
interviews Friday after they announced their long-awaited response
to Paramount's bid. Paramount said Friday it expected ``the
conditions will be satisfied with reasonable promptness'' and said
it would continue to pursue Time.
   Time outlined on Friday a two-stage offer under which it would
pay $70 a share in cash for 100 million Warner shares and then
exchange $70 a share in cash and securities for the remaining 100
million shares of Warner stock.
   A merger of Time and Warner would drive up the cost of acquiring
the company. The acquisition of Warner also would increase Time's
debt load and make it less attractive to would-be bidders.
   Under the agreement announced in March, Time stockholders would
get a share in the new company, Time-Warner Inc., for each Time
share while Warner shareholders would get 0.465 of a share of the
new company for each of their Warner shares.
   Time conceded in its letter that the original Time-Warner merger
plan had accounting and financial advantages because it involved an
exchange of stock.
   But it said shareholders ultimately would benefit from the
revised agreement because the price of their Time stock would rise
after the merger, reflecting the assets and cash flow of the two
companies combined.
   Time stock slumped $9 to $162.50 a share in New York Stock
Exchange consolidated trading Friday, while Warner rose $3.62{ to
$59.25 a share and Paramount fell $1.37{ to $58.12{.
   Analysts said there was still speculation on Wall Street that the
Paramount bid might succeed and that prevented Time stock from
falling further.
</TEXT>
