<FIRST>r a AM-ScoutsRescued     06-17 0203</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scouts Rescued,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boy Scouts Trapped Overnight on Mountain Ridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen Boy Scouts and three troop leaders who
got lost during a heavy rainstorm spent a chilly night on a mountain
ridge before they were rescued by helicopter Saturday.
   ``They're fine. A little bit cold, a little bit hungry and
water-logged, but otherwise okay,'' said Fire Department Capt.
Gardner Brown, pilot of the helicopter, which made five trips to
retrieve the troop.
   ``They were just off to the side of the trail, maybe 50 or 60
feet away, but couldn't see it because of the heavy underbrush,''
Brown said.
   Troop 199 of the Church of Latter-day Saints in Kahuku, a
community across the island of Oahu from Honolulu, began their
62-mile hike across the Koolau Mountain range on Tuesday, planning
to emerge in Kahuku on Saturday.
   The leaders radioed a distress call on a military frequency
Friday afternoon, reporting they were stranded by the weather and
out of food.
   Fire Department and Coast Guard helicopters were unable to locate
them before nightfall despite the constant radio communication.
   The search resumed Saturday and the troop was found located soon
after daylight.
   The scouts ranged in age from 13 to 17.
</TEXT>
