<FIRST>u i AM-EiffelBirthday     06-17 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eiffel Birthday,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paris Celebrates Tower Centennial</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto PAR8</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Ronald Reagan and singer Stevie
Wonder joined hundreds of thousands of Parisians Saturday night in
celebrating the 100th anniversary of the Eiffel Tower.
   The crowd sang ``Happy Birthday'' at the end of an 89-minute
sound, light, and fireworks spectacle _ incorporating special
effects, 100 motorcycles and 5,000 performers _ saluting the
1,000-foot structure erected in 1889.
   Reagan was the guest of Paris Mayor Jacques Chirac, whose city
administration underwrote the $13.3 million cost of the production.
   Singers provided a range of styles _ from Stevie Wonder to
Placido Domingo to French rocker Johnny Halliday and crooner Charles
Trenet.
   Thousands of lights transformed the tower into a luminous
spaceship one minute or a giant brooch of glittering multicolored
jewels the next.
   The spectacle was divided into three parts _ first evoking the
French Revolution of 1789 and the century leading up to the tower's
construction, then the century from 1889 to today and finally the
century of tomorrow (1989-2089).
   Giant screens relayed the show to an estimated 500,000 people who
gathered in the Champs de Mars under the tower, on the Seine bridges
and at the Trocadero across the river.
   The tower's birthday cake measured 65 feet across and 89 feet
high.
   A television special recording the celebration, produced by Radio
City Music Hall Productions, is to be broadcast in France and at
least 18 other countries.
   This was the second celebration this year of the anniversary. On
March 31, the first ascent to the top by Gustave Eiffel and others
was re-eneacted in period dress for a smaller audience.
</TEXT>
