<FIRST>r i AM-Sakharov     06-17 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sakharov,0581</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Activist Says His Country Could See Chinese-Style Crackdown</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND DE LIGNY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRONINGEN, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet activist Andrei Sakharov
said Saturday the Kremlin could someday launch a Chinese-style
crackdown on the Soviet pro-democracy movement.
   ``I fear that in the future, something like it can happen in our
country,'' Sakharov told reporters in this northern Dutch city,
where he was awarded a honorary law degree on Friday.
   ``The political activity of the masses has increased to a very
high degree in the Soviet Union, and the political leadership is
becoming scared,'' the 68-year-old human rights activist said.
   Sakharov received the silver medal of the Dutch Academy of
Sciences in Amsterdam on Saturday.
   Sakharov said there was an ``unprecedented loss of confidence in
the political leaders'' in his country, and he called on Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev to speed the pace of democratic
reforms.
   ``That is the only way to avoid a disaster. ... The country is on
the brink of catastrophe.''
   ``Nothing has been achieved during the 72 years of power monopoly
by the Communist Party which cost tens of millions of lives,'' he
said. ``There is no economic structure, no opportunity for
technological progress, and no social justice.''
   Sakharov's remarks in Russian were translated into Dutch by a
Groningen University interpreter.
   The nuclear physicist, who was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in
1975 for his human rights efforts, called on the Soviet leadership
to support the pro-democracy movement in China.
   ``Such support would reinforce the campaign for democratic change
in the Soviet Union,'' he said.
   Chinese troops crushed the movement in Beijing on June 3-4.
Estimates differ on how many died. The Chinese government variously
says 200 to 300 people, mostly soldiers, were killed. Unofficial
Chinese and Western intelligence reports say troops fired on unarmed
crowds and killed up to 3,000.
   Gorbachev, in his most extensive comments since visiting China
last month, said this week that the Soviet leadership regretted some
aspects of the conflict in China and expressed concerns over the
future of reforms there.
   Gorbachev allowed Sakharov to return to Moscow in December 1986
after nearly seven years in exile in Gorky. Sakharov supported
Gorbachev early on but has become increasingly critical, saying that
democratic reforms are being hampered by conservatives and that
Gorbachev himself has not gone far enough.
   For instance, Sakharov was among those saying that Gorbachev's
election as president and Communist Party general secretary
concentrated too much power in one man's hands. Nevertheless,
Sakharov has returned to official good favor.
   He was given his old job back at the Academy of Sciences, where
he works as a physicist, has been quoted frequently in the official
press, spoken at officially sponsored news conferences, and been
allowed to travel to the West.
   Gorbachev has shown respect for Sakharov, but at the recent
Soviet Congress meeting, Gorbachev criticized Sakharov for saying
the session was a failure.
   Sakharov's journey to the Netherlands is his third trip abroad.
He is accompanied by his wife, Yelena Bonner.
   On Friday, he accepted an honorary law degree from the State
University in Groningen, 120 miles northeast of Amsterdam. He was
cited for his ``exceptional services to the cause of ... human
rights.''
   On Sunday, Sakharov and Ms. Bonner are to fly to London to visit
friends, said Rob Rutgers, dean of the university's law faculty.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
