<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Elections     06-17 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Elections,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communists and Solidarity Prepare for Runoff Elections Sunday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party hopes to recover a
shred of dignity and Solidarity another triumph in Sunday's runoff
elections for parliamentary seats undecided in the first round of
voting two weeks ago.
   In the June 4 balloting, Solidarity-backed candidates won 252 of
the 261 seats allotted to the opposition in the new National
Assembly.
   There are contests Sunday for only eight seats in the new
100-member Senate where opposition candidates were allowed to run in
all races and won 92.
   In the Sejm, the existing Parliament, opposition candidates were
allowed to run for 161 of the 460 seats and the 299 remaining seats
were set aside for candidates of the Communist Party and its allies.
   Opposition candidates won 160 seats, leaving only one open for
the runoff, but the communists and their allies won only five of the
seats allotted to them and voters will decide on the 294 other seats
in the runoff.
   To win a seat under procedures agreed to in an April agreement by
the communist government and Solidarity, a winner had to receive a
majority of the vote. The agreement, providing for Poland's freest
elections in more than four decades, also legalized the Solidarity
union movement that had been suppressed under martial law in 1981
and then outlawed.
   Solidarity has adopted a strategy of backing reform candidates in
the runoff races involving the seats set aside for the communists.
   ``We have learned the taste of victory,'' Solidarity leader Lech
Walesa told the union's National Executive Commission at a meeting
Saturday in Gdansk.
   He said of the June 4 elections: ``Society gave us more than we
wanted and now the main thing is to build the union.''
   Although nearly all of Sunday's contests involve seats reserved
for the communists and their allies, Solidarity has been campaigning
for a strong voter turnout.
   ``They will be our partners in the Sejm,'' Solidarity spokesman
Janusz Onyszkiewicz said Friday of the communists. ``One cannot be
indifferent to what these partners will be like. It could be
worthwhile to support someone. It could be worthwhile to cross
someone out.''
   Opposition publications have listed at least 59 communist or
allied candidates considered sympathetic to Solidarity.
   Those liberal candidates could combine with Solidarity's elected
deputies to create a powerful bloc in the Sejm and work with the
union's overwhelming Senate majority.
   Prime Minister Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski has been trying to put the
pieces back together after the crushing defeats in the first round.
   In a speech last week he called the June 4 results a one-time
aberration attributable to Communist Party mistakes and poor
economic conditions that he said made many Poles ``pin exaggerated
hopes on the opposition.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
