<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--MarcosSurgery     06-17 0129</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Marcos Surgery,0132</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marcos in Critical Condition after Surgery to Stop Bleeding Ulcer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine president Ferdinand Marcos
underwent surgery Saturday to stop a bleeding gastric ulcer, a
hospital spokesman said. He was listed in critical condition.
   Marcos, 71, was recovering in the intensive care unit of St.
Francis Medical Center and was conscious but not alert, said Eugene
Tiwanak, assistant hospital administrator.
   Marcos has been hospitalized since January and has remained on
life support equipment since suffering cardiac, lung and kidney
failure last month.
   The deposed president and his wife Imelda, 59, are under U.S.
indictment for racketeering. They are charged with funneling $100
million dollars from the Philippine treasury to the United States.
   They have been lived in exile in Hawaii since 1986.
</TEXT>
