<FIRST>u i AM-Europarliament     06-17 0302</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Europarliament,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Seven Nations Vote In European Parliament Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINA MACKENZIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in seven nations of the European
Economic Community determine on Sunday who to send to the European
Parliament.
   The balloting takes place in Belgium, West Germany, Greece,
France, Luxembourg, Italy and Portugal.
   Official results from Thursday's balloting in the five other EEC
nations _ Ireland, Britain, Denmark, Spain and the Netherlands _ are
to be reported after Sunday's round of voting ends. In all, more
than 7,000 candidates are running.
   Exit polls from the voting Thursday indicated socialists and
centrist Christian Democrats scored some gains, largely at the
expense of conservatives.
   Although it is still mainly a consultative body, the 518-member
Parliament received more powers in 1987 and could play a major role
in the trading bloc's efforts to forge a single borderless market by
late 1992.
   Because of the voting schedule and time differences in the EEC,
the final official count will not be known until sometime Monday.
   This is the schedule:
   First results, including those from Spain and the Netherlands
that voted Thursday, will be reported Sunday night after the polls
close in Italy, France, Portugal, Luxembourg, Belgium and Greece.
   About four hours later, results will be announced from West
Germany and all of Britain except Northern Ireland. The Northern
Ireland vote will be announced around noon Monday along with the
outcome in the republic of Ireland.
   The complete Danish vote will not be announced until early Monday
morning.
   Socialist deputies held 166 seats and formed the largest bloc in
the former Parliament while Christian Democrats had 112.
   There were 7,126 candidates, representing 178 political parties
in the EEC nations, in the Thursday and Sunday balloting.
   The Parliament meets one week each month in the French city of
Strasbourg.
</TEXT>
