<SECOND>AM-Shooting Spree, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0561,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Dead, Two Wounded in Shooting Spree</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Allen fired...,' to CORRECT to Cantrell, sted
Allen.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELCH, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly man killed three people, including
his sister, and began firing at police before he was shot to death,
authorities said.
   Conrad Cantrell, 67, had five loaded guns and more than 500
rounds of ammunition in his car and was firing two pistols, one in
each hand, when he was killed Friday by authorities in rural
southwestern West Virginia, said McDowell County Sheriff's Deputy
R.L. Blevins.
   Cantrell, described as an unemployed sawmill worker, allegedly
went to his sister's house Friday afternoon and shot her and her
husband to death. The victims were identified as Hershel
Picklesimer, 70, and his wife, June, 69. Mrs. Picklesimer was
Cantrell's sister.
   About 20 minutes later, Charlie Ball of Man was shot and killed
and his wife, Juanita, was seriously wounded, authorities said.
Cantrell also knew the Balls, police said.
   Mrs. Ball, 58, was in listed stable condition Saturday morning at
Man Appalachian Regional Hospital.
   After the Balls were shot, Cantrell fled and refused to pull over
when police spotted him on West Virginia 16. A roadblock was set up.
   At the roadblock, Cantrell jumped out of his car, and McDowell
County Deputy Donald Hicks ``ordered him to drop the gun and put his
hands on the dashboard,'' McDowell County Sheriff R.J. Allen said.
``When he did, Cantrell opened fire on the deputy and everything
went crazy from there.''
   Cantrell fired several times at Hicks and other officers, and
they shot back and killed him, police said.
   One officer, Chief Deputy Charles Lawson, suffered a gunshot
wound above the elbow, and the shot broke his arm. He was listed in
stable condition this morning at Humana Hospital St. Lukes in
Bluefield, a nursing supervisor said.
   Police did not know what might have brought about the shootings.
</TEXT>
