<FIRST>r i AM-Mexico-Journalist     06-17 0281</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Journalist,0293</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Federal Police Head Indicted In Killing of Journalist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jose Antonio Zorrilla, once head of Mexico's
Federal Security Department, was indicted for murder Saturday in the
slaying of an investigative journalist five years ago.
   Prosecutor Rafael Avanti contends Zorrilla, 47, was the
mastermind of the killing of newspaper columnist Manuel Buendia in
May 30, 1984.
   Avanti said that during the indictment proceedings in the 34th
Penal Court Judge Roberto Hernandez Martinez ordered Zorrilla held
for trial.
   In presenting the case the prosecution said Buendia was slain
because Zorrilla feared the journalist would expose links to some of
Mexico's major drug traffickers.
   At the time of the slaying Zorrilla was the chief of the Federal
Security Department, the equivalent of the FBI in the United States.
The department was dismantled in 1985 because of alleged corruption.
   Zorrilla had been arraigned Friday and told reporters after the
arraignment, ``I did not kill my friend and there is no evidence
that implicates me.'' He did not enter a plea at the indictment
hearing, Avanti said.
   If convicted of homicide, Zorrilla could be sentenced to up to 40
years in prison.
   Authorities have said Zorrilla was one of the first law
enforcement officers at the scene of the shooting of Buendia. They
also said they have in custody the gunman who shot the journalist,
but they have not identified him or given other details.
   Zorrilla said Friday he believed Buendia was killed because his
columns in the newspaper Excelsior dealt with ``very delicate
subjects.''
   Among the subjects Buendia wrote about were corruption in high
places, drug trafficking, gun smuggling and the CIA.
</TEXT>
