<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 2222EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-CoalStrike     06-17 0430</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Coal Strike,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trumka Calls on Pittston Chief to Negotiate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEG THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Mine Workers President Richard
Trumka renewed his call Saturday for The Pittston Co. to help end a
coal strike that has expanded into wildcat walkouts by more than
20,000 miners in six states.
   Coal fields in the region were mostly quiet Saturday, a day when
production slacks off at most mines before they close down for
Sunday. No new walkouts were reported.
   In southern West Virginia, a labor group affiliated with the
AFL-CIO put together a truck caravan Saturday to take food to
striking miners.
   In a letter to Pittston Co. Chairman Paul Douglas, Trumka
rejected Pittston's assertion that contract talks are at an impasse.
   ``Impasse can only be reached after the parties have engaged in
full good faith negotiations that leave each side with no more
flexibility on the issues at stake. That is not the case here,''
Trumka wrote.
   ``First, Pittston has not engaged in good faith negotiations.
Secondly, the union continues to remain flexible on working out the
differences between us.''
   Pittston last week declared negotiations at an impasse, which
allowed it to implement its latest contract offer. Federal labor law
requires UMW leaders to present that offer to their membership.
   Pittston also restored benefit payments to about 1,500 retirees,
widows and disabled miners. The company had cut off those benefits
when its contract expired in February 1988.
   Trumka told Douglas the gesture was appreciated, but said it was
not enough. ``Pittston's actions are too little, too late,'' he
wrote.
   Douglas said he had not received the letter ``and nothing
(Trumka) now says can change that situation.''
   About 1,600 UMW members went on strike against the Pittston Coal
Group Inc., a subsidiary of The Pittston Co., in West Virginia and
Virginia on April 5. Other miners began unauthorized walkouts Monday
in southern West Virginia in sympathy with the Pittston strikers.
   By Saturday, the wildcat walkouts had idled about two-thirds of
West Virginia's 24,000 miners and miners in Pennsylvania, Indiana,
Virginia, Kentucky and Tennessee.
   The West Virginia Labor Solidarity Committee on Saturday drove
several truckloads of food from Charleston to strikers in Logan and
Beckley. The 50 committee members in the caravan also planned to
join picket lines after delivering the food, said spokeswoman Elaine
Harris.
   The caravan was part of a nationwide call by the AFL-CIO to help
the striking miners. Tractor-trailer trucks bearing food from union
members in Pennsylvania are expected to arrive next week, Harris
said.
   ``This is just the start,'' she said.
</TEXT>
