<FIRST>r a AM-HelicopterCrash 2ndLd-Writethru a0601 06-17 0506</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Helicopter Crash, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0601,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>Guard Helicopter Crashes; Six Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, `Joe Covolo..., to UPDATE with identities of
last two victims.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YARMOUTH, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Guard helicopter crashed in
dense fog early Saturday, killing all six crewmen and just missing
homes in this Cape Cod tourist haven, authorities said.
   The UH-1 Bell helicopter cut a 20-foot wide path through the
woods before crashing, throwing its doors, glass and other debris
more than 30 feet. The cockpit was shattered beyond recognition, and
doors and glass were found 20 feet away.
   ``We said, `This guy's going to crash,' and a couple of seconds
later he did,'' said witness John Palino. The helicopter missed his
home by about 100 feet, crashing behind a neighbor's home.
   ``It was like a crumpled piece of paper,'' Palino said. ``We
didn't want to get near it because we were afraid it would explode.''
   Palino said he and his son went with flashlights and found two
bodies on the ground. ``The ones we saw you could tell they were
really young,'' he said.
   Three victims were members of a Delaware Army National Guard unit
from New Castle, Del., that had just completed the first week of an
annual two-week training exercise at Camp Edwards in Mashpee.
   Delaware guard spokeswoman Terry Blevins identified them as 1st
Lt. David Joseph Hendry, 26, and Chief Warrant Officer Hugh Bryan
Pearce, 35, both of Wilmington, and Staff Sgt. Benjamin Robert
Greenplate, 40, of Newark, Del.
   Another victim was identified as Sgt. Ward Arthur Cornell, 43, of
Mansfield, Conn., said Maj. Gen. John T. Gereski, Connecticut's
adjutant general.
   The other two victims were from a Richmond unit, the 80th
Maneuver Training Command, and were identified as Master Sgt. Robert
E. Lucey Jr. of Emporia, Va., and Spec. Samuel K. May of Richmond,
said Virginia Army Reserve spokeswoman Maj. Mari K. Eder. No ages
were immediately available, she said.
   The helicopter crashed shortly after midnight Saturday while
returning to the camp from Rhode Island's main commercial airport in
Warwick, said Army spokeswoman 1st. Lt. Colleen Hammond.
   The helicopter had left Camp Edwards at 6:45 p.m. Friday to pick
up a military official due in at T.F. Greene Airport on a commercial
flight from Philadelphia, Hammond said. After waiting two hours, the
helicopter crew learned the flight was grounded and decided to
return to the base.
   ``That's the last we know,'' Hammond said.
   The helicopter went down about 30 miles from the camp, she said.
Army officials said the cause of the crash was being investigated.
   Neighbors said they could tell the helicopter was having trouble.
   ``You could hear the blades stopping and (then) like a thump,''
neighbor Bill O'Connor said.
   Kenneth Chesley said he slept through the crash, but his wife,
who was watching television, said their entire house vibrated.
   Yarmouth's winter population of 20,000 swells to 80,000 with the
onset of tourist season, police said. The town is approximately 85
miles south of Boston.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
