<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 2318EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Mayors 1stLd-Writethru a0523 06-17 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayors, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0523,0689</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors to Bush: Are You Listening?</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf, `Republican Mayor...,' to CORRECT mayor's name
to Isaac, sted Isaacs.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's mayors, after eight years of
complaining that they were ignored by the White House, searched for
signs the Bush administration will be more responsive as they
gathered for their annual meeting Saturday.
   ``We feel the needs of the people of our major cities have not
been given the priority that they should have been'' over the past
decade, said Mayor Kathy Whitmire of Houston.
   President Bush declined an invitation to attend the annual
meeting of the U.S. Conference of Mayors, a convention of more than
200 elected urban leaders that runs through Wednesday.
   Two of his Cabinet secretaries and other administration officials
planned to address the mayors, who have asked the administration to
outline how it intends to establish its national urban policy.
   ``We spent a good deal of our time under the Reagan
administration trying to save our programs,'' said J. Thomas
Cochran, executive director of the conference. ``Now we're in a
situation where Mr. Bush has been elected and we're trying to see
what a kinder and gentler administration will mean.''
   Dealing with drugs, AIDS and homelessness are among the top
concerns on the mayors' agendas. Cochran said many mayors believe
their cities are the front lines in those battles and that they were
not given enough voice in the previous administration's handling of
them.
   ``Those are three very lonely issues,'' Cochran said in an
interview. ``We believe we've been setting national policy. It is
only fair that if Congress is going to come forth on housing or
drugs that we be involved. ... We'd like to be back at the table.''
   Republican Mayor Bob Isaac of Colorado Springs, Colo., said at an
opening news conference that the absence of Bush and Vice President
Dan Quayle should not be read as a lack of administration interest
in urban problems.
   Some Democratic mayors were inclined to agree _ but suggested
they expected better in the future.
   ``In fairness, the president was abroad most recently and he's
got to weigh his schedule,'' said Mayor Joseph Riley of the host
city, a former president of the group and leading urban advocate.
   ``I wouldn't let the fact that the first year they didn't come
make a statement,'' he said. ``Hopefully, they'll make it next year.
But if not, then there might be reason to be concerned.''
   Whitmire, a Democrat who is in line to become president of the
group this week, said mayors ``are certainly optimistic'' and have
found ``the doors to be open'' so far in the new administration.
   Housing and Urban Development Secretary Jack Kemp, whose
department has been rocked by charges of multimillion-dollar fraud
and influence peddling during the Reagan adminisration, is scheduled
to address the mayors Monday. Transportation Secretary Samuel
Skinner and Environmental Protection Agency Administrator William K.
Reilly are to speak Tuesday.
   Bush's new proposals to cut acid rain and curb urban smog are
among the issues on the mayors' agenda. Others include crime, day
care, housing, mass transit, regulation of cable television and
maintaining congressional support for the remaining federal urban
aid programs.
   The mayors will vote on dozens of resolutions, including one
proposal that calls for increased federal aid and cuts in defense
spending as a way to provide more aid for urban programs.
   The troubles at HUD may be aired at a workshop the mayors plan,
although mayors avoided any criticism of HUD's previous management
at an opening news conference.
   The HUD scandals are a blow to cities, however, because the
department is the agency that handles much of the federal aid
flowing to urban America and is the principal advocate within the
government for many of those programs.
   A frequent lament from mayors has been the Reagan
administration's fiscal assault on federal housing programs, in
which cuts in HUD's budget authority amounted to 80 percent when
adjusted for inflation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
