<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--GyrocopterCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0600 06-17 0194</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gyrocopter Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0600,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gyrocopter Crashes in Lake; Two Killed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with identities of victims.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A homemade gyrocopter crashed into a lake
Saturday, killing two people, authorities said.
   The bodies of a Kentucky couple were recovered from Acton Lake at
Hueston Woods State Park, said Park Manager Joel Udstuen. They were
identified as Robert W. Wahn, 56, and his wife Betty, 48, both of
Verona.
   Mike Stein of the Ohio State Patrol aviation division said
gyrocopters differ from helicopters in that a helicopter's engine
drives the overhead rotor, while a gyrocopter's engine drives a rear
rotor, Stein said. Backwash from the gyrocopter's rear blade powers
the overhead rotor.
   Pilots of gyrocopters must have a pilot's license and register
their aircraft with the Federal Aviation Administration.
   Witness Sally Phillipson said she and a friend were walking by
the lake when they heard an engine sputtering. Ms. Phillipson said
she saw the aircraft lose a rotor and plunge into the waters of the
lake.
   Udstuen said officers recovered a fuselage and a rotor blade.
   The park is located near the Ohio-Indiana border.
</TEXT>
