<FIRST>u i AM-Nicaragua-US 1stLd-Writethru a0565 06-17 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0565,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua to Require Visas for U.S. Citizens; Noriega Urges Against
Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 9 grafs to UPDATE with Ortega, Noriega comments.
Pickup 6th graf `The Sandinista...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. citizens need visas to enter
Nicaragua beginning July 1, and President Daniel Ortega said
Saturday the measure is necessary to prevent Washington from
meddling in his country's affairs.
   Panama's de facto leader, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, on
Saturday urged Nicaragua not to hold elections as scheduled next
February because of what he described as U.S. interference.
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Lou Falino declined comment on the visa
requirement, and officials with the Foreign Ministry, which
announced the measure late Friday, were not available.
   The leftist government has expressed suspicion that the United
States may attempt to affect the outcome of the February elections.
   The opposition newspaper La Prensa said in its Saturday editions
that the visa requirement is ``a legal formula to prevent an
avalanche of U.S. journalists and political observers from coming to
analyze and observe what occurs in our elections.''
   Ortega, speaking in a Managua suburb, said his government will
require visiting Americans to visas ``because the employees of the
yanqui government continue to abuse the hospitality'' of Nicaragua.
He said Washington continues to ``conspire against the people of
Nicaragua.''
   Noriega, head of Panama's Defense Forces, said the United States
participated in irregularities during Panama's May 7 elections,
which international observers say the opposition won but the
government nullified.
   ``Nicaragua: keep your eyes open. Don't be fools. Don't hold
elections because they will repeat the same medicine of Panama,''
Noriega told parlimentarians from 10 Latin American countries
meeting in David, 250 miles west of Panama City.
   Barricada, the official newspaper of the ruling Sandinista party,
and El Nuevo Diario, a pro-government dailyand El Nuevo Diario have
published stories in the past few days about a ``secret plan'' to
funnel $3 million to Nicaragua's opposition parties.
   The Sandinista government has said several times that the
February elections will be a ``political confrontation'' with the
United States, which supports the Nicaraguan rebels known as Contras.
   Earlier this month the Foreign Ministry said U.S. diplomats will
not be allowed to act as election observers. ``To invite them would
be the equivalent of asking the fox to guard the henhouse,'' it said.
   It also said the American diplomats could not attend opposition
party meetings or rallies.
   Nicaragua has twice expelled U.S. diplomats over the past year,
accusing them of interfering in its internal affairs.
   In May it expelled Kathleen Williamson Barnon, a labor attache,
and economic attache Joel Franklin Cassman saying they tried ``to
manipulate'' teachers into a nationwide strike.
   The U.S. responded six days later by expelling two Nicaraguan
diplomats, Wiliam Vigil and Roberto Vargas.
   In July last year, a large opposition rally brought about another
series of expulsions. Nicaragua ordered U.S. Ambassador Richard
Melton and seven other diplomats to leave and Washington retaliated
by expelling the Nicaraguan ambassador.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
