<FIRST>r i AM-BRF---Bahrain-Stocks     06-17 0143</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF---Bahrain-Stocks,0148</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bahrain Opens Stock Exchange</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Commerce Minister Habib Qassem on Saturday
opened Bahrain's first official stock exchange and 12,000 shares
changed hands in the first 30 minutes of trading.
   The island state is a banking and service center for many
countries in the Persian Gulf region.
   Qassem, who heads the stock exchange board, told a news
conference, ``We're aspiring for development and expansion ....
We're very optimistic.''
   Market monitor Ibrahim Janahi recorded the initial deals on a
wall-length blackboard listing 29 Bahrain-registered companies.
   They have a combined total of 4.4 billion shares with a value
placed at $1.6 billion.
   The market will operate from 9.30 a.m. to 11.00 a.m. every day
except Fridays, the Moslem holiday.
   Bahrain is a member of the Gulf Cooperation Council that includes
Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Qatar, Oman and the United Arab Emirates.
</TEXT>
