<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Regents-Commercials     06-17 0466</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Regents-Commercials,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Regents Ban ``Channel One'' From New York Classrooms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BAUDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The New York Board of Regents on Friday
banned a commercial-laden news program from the state's high
schools, becoming the second state in the nation to frown on the
project.
   The regents rejected Whittle Communications' ``Channel One''
program, saying they were worried the ``active commercialization''
of the programs would send the wrong message to high school students.
   The 12-minute news program contains two minutes of commercials
for candy, jeans, acne cream and other products aimed at teen-agers.
In return for an agreement to show the daily programs, Whittle wired
high schools with complete closed circuit television systems,
including satellite dishes, televisions and videocassette recorders.
   ``It's a very tempting package that has a flaw,'' state Education
Commissioner Thomas Sobol.
   The decision is a blow to the Tennessee-based Whittle, which has
said it needs to sign up 40 percent of the nation's high schools if
``Channel One'' was to be successful. Earlier this month, California
officials threatened their schools with a loss of funding if they
signed contracts with Whittle.
   Some regents also expressed anger with Whittle's aggressive
lobbying in support of ``Channel One.'' Edward Meyer of Westchester
County charged that some members of the education board told him
Whittle had offered them jobs or consulting contracts if they
supported the project.
   Meyer declined to name the regents involved and several other
regents interviewed denied any knowledge of such offers. Laura
Eshbaugh, executive vice president for Whittle Communications, said
she knew nothing about any offers.
   Eshbaugh said she was disappointed with the decision by the New
York board, but said ``Channel One'' would be able to survive the
rejection.
   Whittle had increased its offer to the regents and taken its case
to the public in the days leading to Friday morning's board meeting.
The company ran two full-page advertisements in The New York Times,
and Meyer said some regents were bombarded by ``junk fax'' messages
in support of Whittle.
   Whittle offered to donate 1,000 hours of satellite time so other
educational programming could be shown in schools, education
department officials said. The company also said it would pay
$500,000 to New York's Public Broadcasting System.
   But Whittle wouldn't take out the commercials.
   Several regents said they worried the commercials would cause
poor students who couldn't afford items advertised to feel
inadequate. They also said the program seems geared to suburban
students instead of the more troubled city schools that need the
technology Whittle could provide.
   But Eshbaugh said schools contain many forms of advertising, such
as wall posters, yearbook advertisements and brand names emblazoned
on the clothing students wear.
   ``Commercialization is there,'' she said. ``However any of us
might not like it there, it's there to stay.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
