<FILEID>AP-NR-06-17-89 0112EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     06-17 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Political Opposition Accepts Dialogue Offer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAFAEL CANDANEDO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The political opposition accepted on
Friday a proposal for a three-sided dialogue with the government and
military that was proposed by the Organization of American States.
   The Defense Forces have not signaled whether they will accept,
however.
   Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, commander of the Defense Forces and
Panama's de facto leader, has said repeatedly the military is
unwilling to take part in negotiations and that civilian government
officials should hold the discussions.
   The opposition has said the military must be included in any
settlement talks because Noriega holds real power here.
   At a lunch with businessmen, opposition presidential candidate
Guillermo Endara read a declaration accepting the OAS proposal.
   ``We are willing to initiate immediate direct conversations with
the Defense Forces and its commander-in-chief, so that we can reach
a national accord that assures the transfer of power by September
1989,'' he read.
   An OAS delegation concluded a three-day visit to Panama on
Wednesday. The mission followed a previous OAS visit in May to end
Panama's political crisis.
   International observers said the opposition won May 7 elections.
The government nullified the election, citing foreign intervention.
   Endara and vice presidential candidate Guillermo Ford signed the
declaration with the titles of president-elect and vice
president-elect.
   Noriega told the four OAS negotiators U.S. intransigence was to
blame for Panama's problems.
   The mission is to deliver a report on its findings at a July 19
meeting of OAS foreign ministers.
   Noriega was indicted in Florida last year on federal
drug-trafficking and money-laundering charges. He denies the
charges. Then-President Eric Arturo Delvalle tried to fire him, but
Noriega orchestrated Delvalle's ouster.
   The United States has tried to force Noriega out. It froze more
than $140 million in Panamanian bank deposits and canal payments,
hobbling the banking industry and leaving the government
ill-equipped to meet payrolls or fund basic social programs.
</TEXT>
