<HEAD>Canada Reports Chinese Officials Defect</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some officials from the Chinese Embassy in Ottawa
have requested refugee status in Canada, Foreign Affairs Minister
Joe Clark said Friday.
   Clark would not say how many Chinese diplomatic staff had asked,
and he declined to say if there have been defections among the
staffs of the Chinese consulates in Toronto and Vancouver.
   ``I can confirm that there have been approaches by some officials
of the Chinese Embassy indicating the desire to stay in Canada,'' he
told reporters outside the House of Commons. ``I don't propose to
discuss names or numbers or locations or any details.
   A source told The Canadian Press that five officials from the
embassy and two from the consulate in Vancouver had asked as of
Thursday to remain in Canada.
   The foreign minister said requests from Chinese for refugee
status will be handled sympathetically.
   Clark met Thursday with Chinese Ambassador Zhang Wenpu to
protest, for the second time this month, the actions taken by China
against students and others seeking greater democracy.
   Canada also recalled its ambassador, Earl Drake, for
consultations.
