<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 19,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Mon June 19</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Optimists' Rallying Cry: ``Soft Landing''</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If there is a single theme that dominates talk
about the U.S. economy so far in 1989, it is embodied in the catch
phrase ``soft landing.''
   For months now, investors and business planners have been
debating whether the Federal Reserve can pull the trick off _
bringing the high-flying economy down to earth without a hard impact
that inflicts a lot of pain.
   Some skeptics dismiss the whole idea as a dangerous fantasy, the
kind of delusion that prompts companies to build new factories just
before orders suddenly dry up or speculators to buy stocks at a
market top.
   The business cycle hasn't been abolished, these observers say,
and sooner or later there will have to be a recession to wring out
the excesses of a long period of expansion.
   The doubters say they speak from long experience. But Maury
Harris, economist at the investment firm of PaineWebber Inc., says
they are overlooking two emphatic ``soft landing'' precedents in
very recent economic history.
   ``This current soft landing is a replay of the experiences in
1984-86 and 1966-67,'' he contends.
   ``Following a tighter Federal Reserve System monetary policy,
growth slowed and, because the economy was not at `full employment,'
inflation slowed enough to allow a drop in interest rates sufficient
to sustain growth.''
   One problem some people have in buying the idea of a soft
landing, Harris says, is that the term has never been clearly
defined.
   There is a formal description of recession, as monitored by the
National Bureau of Economic Research: two consecutive quarters of
declines in the nation's gross national product, after adjustment
for inflation.
   A soft landing, by contrast, has no such specific
characteristics. It might be called a non-recession, rather than a
tangible event.
   Also, Harris says, many analysts assume that the economy has
reached ``full employment'' _ a point where inflation can't be tamed
without stern measures that must almost certainly hurt business
activity.
   ``Our view for some time has been that the economy is not at
`full employment,''' Harris says. ``If we were at full employment,
wages would be rising a lot faster than the modest 3.8 percent rise
over the past year.''
   Stan Shipley and Robert Barbera, economists at Shearson Lehman
Hutton Inc., say confusion is natural in a period when a soft
landing occurs.
   ``As the economy downshifts from rapid growth to more moderate
growth, economic statistics can be mixed,'' they observe.
   ``Often, within one month, a conflicting picture of the economy
emerges, with evidence of strength contrasted by evidence of
weakness.''
   A case in point is the index of leading economic indicators, the
government's statistical means of trying to gauge future trends. The
index was down in February and March, but rebounded strongly in
April with a 0.8 percent rise.
   When the May figure is reported later this month, it is expected
to show another drop.
   Over the last year, however, the index has edged up 2.1 percent.
That points, say Shipley and Barbera, to ``a soft landing, not a
recession.''
   Harris, for his part, acknowledges that there is ``an
understandable tendency to deny that the Fed can `fine tune' the
economy.
   ``However,'' he maintains, ``if we're not at full employment and
quite positive real interest rates allow the potential for sharp
rate declines, if necessary, there's lots of room for reversible and
nonfatal errors in Fed policies before there's too much inflation
followed by a recession.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Mon June 19</NOTE>
