<FIRST>a f BC-LittlePittsburgh Adv18   06-17 0930</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Little Pittsburgh, Adv 18,0961</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday June 18 and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>One-Time `Little Pittsburgh' Tries To Regroup As `Little Silicon
Valley'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GERMAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TROY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The land that spawned the detachable collar and
the nation's steel industry is losing a leading drug research firm
the same way it lost bustling mills and textile plants.
   Sterling Drug Inc. is pulling 1,200 jobs out of its operation in
East Greenbush, crimping Rensselaer County's plans to make the area
once called ``Little Pittsburgh'' into ``Little Silicon Valley.''
   ``Troy was more than `Little Pittsburgh,''' said Timothy Hulburt,
president of the Rensselaer County Chamber of Commerce. ``It was the
first Pittsburgh. Pittsburgh was the second Troy.''
   In the 1800s, the trio of cities at the Hudson and Mohawk rivers
_ Troy, Watervliet and Cohoes _ was ideally situated to become a
major industrial center. In mid-19th century America, Troy mills
pioneered the Bessemer process of converting iron to steel, a method
quickly adopted nationwide.
   Troy ironmaster Henry Burden built the world's biggest hydropower
waterwheel, and his mills churned out a horseshoe every second,
shodding almost all the horses used by the North in the Civil War.
   In 1826, Troy housewife Hannah Montague, tired of washing her
husband's shirts when only the collars were dirty, invented the
detachable collar. That sparked a new industry and earned Troy the
nickname, ``Collar City.''
   About 50 years ago, the mills and textile plants began a slow
fade to the South. By the mid-1970s, the Troy area resembled a relic
of an industrial center with little prosperity.
   ``This area was thriving and bustling with small industries that
have disappeared from the face of the earth,'' said Bill Coomley, a
lifelong Troy resident.
   Local officials say they're disappointed at the decision by
Sterling's owner, Eastman Kodak Co., to move the pharmaceutical
research and production plants to the Philadelphia area. But they
say many firms could take Sterling's place as Rensselaer County's
biggest high-tech employer.
   Sterling plans a gradual withdrawal over two years of its 950
research jobs and 260 production jobs. The research workers will
have the chance to relocate in Pennsylvania. The production workers
won't.
   Technology companies are so eager to come to Rensselaer County
``that if all (Sterling's) people were gone tomorrow, I could have
that land filled up in a month,'' said County Executive John Buono.
   Because of such institutions as Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute,
the country's oldest engineering school, Troy and its environs have
attracted pioneers in the major industries of tomorrow, officials
said.
   ``This area has a rich tradition of innovation,'' said Michael
Wacholder, director of RPI's Rensselaer Technology Park, which
houses 35 companies dabbling in the world's most advanced technology.
   The days of the Bessemer process and detachable collar are gone,
but the Troy area is again at the leading edge of new ideas, he said.
   ``What we're seeing is just a repeat of what happened in Troy in
the last century,'' he said. ``Now we're just on to another era.''
   One firm at the technology park, U.S. Composites, is developing
strong, lightweight composites that may replace steel in auto
production, Wacholder said.
   About 1,000 people work in the 6-year-old park, selected as one
of the country's five top such facilities by the national
Association of University Related Research Parks. Some of the
businesses employ as many as 350 people, while others have only two
or three.
   But the pioneering research each of those companies is doing now
could blossom into major industries, turning today's two-man shop
into tomorrow's 2,000-man shop, Wacholder said.
   Rensselaer County's jobless rate was 4.8 percent in April, vs.
5.6 percent statewide and 5.1 percent nationwide.
   Like most parts of the country, Rensselaer County is seeing a
rise in service sector jobs that generally pay far less than the
manufacturing jobs that have left the area.
   Since 1982, the number of manufacturing jobs has been virtually
unchanged at about 6,600, said Labor Department spokesman James
Ross. Since 1982, the number of service jobs has grown by 25 percent
to 12,635 in March, he said.
   Those service jobs, officials hope, will continue to make up for
the well-paying blue-collar jobs that inevitably disappear. The last
of Troy's textile jobs will be gone in July as Cluett Peabody &amp; Co.,
maker of Arrow shirts, moves its last 385 local jobs to plants in
Georgia.
   Recruiting employees for businesses at the technology park often
involves no more than contacting RPI or nearby Hudson Valley
Community College, which stresses technology programs. Many of the
businesses, including U.S. Composites, were founded by RPI graduates
who set up shop in the area to be near its educational resources.
   Ironically, Sterling says it's moving because Rensselaer County
doesn't have the pool of trained drug researchers and the high-tech
pharmaceutical facilities that Philadelphia and nearby southern New
Jersey offer.
   New York officials shrug off the apparent slap at the area's
research resources.
   ``I think they kind of misspeak when they use that,'' Buono said.
``They want to go to Philly to raid existing pharmaceutical
companies so they can build their staff faster.''
   Unlike the mass pullouts by heavy industry from the Northeast
since the 1960s, Sterling's exodus is an isolated incident that
won't be a big obstacle to creating ``little Silicon Valley,'' local
officials say.
   ``Whenever I heard people talk about businesses moving from the
Northeast to the Sunbelt, I'd say, `This is the brain-belt,''
Wacholder said. ``The brains in the Northeast developed the
technology being used in California and the South. The brain-belt
survives.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday June 18</NOTE>
