<HEAD>For release weekend editions June 17-18</HEAD>
<HEAD>UNDATED: year ago.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Here are some commodity price trends for the past week.
   Wheat for delivery in July settled Friday at $3.94\ a bushel on
the Chicago Board of Trade, up from $3.86{ a week earlier; July corn
rallied to $2.62} a bushel from $2.51}; July oats climbed to $1.64{
a bushel from $1.62{; and July soybeans advanced to $7.33 a bushel
from $7.02{.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, June live cattle rose to
71.70 cents a pound from 69.82 cents; August feeder cattle improved
to 80.97 cents a pound from 79.95 cents; June live hogs rallied to
48.22 cents a pound from 47.90 cents; July frozen pork bellies rose
to 33.92 cents a pound from 31.90 cents.
   On New York's Commodity Exchange, August gold settled at $368.80
cents a troy ounce, compared with $362 a week earlier; July silver
rose to $5.305 a troy ounce from $5.19.
   In energy futures trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange,
West Texas Intermediate crude oil for July delivery rose to $19.95 a
barrel from $19.88; July heating oil fell to 45.71 cents a gallon
from 47.03 cents; July unleaded gasoline plunged to 58.14 cents a
gallon from 63.72 cents.
