<FIRST>d f PM-Time     06-17 0836</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Time,0867</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Time Responds to Paramount Bid with $14 Billion Offer for Warner</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paramount Communications Inc. says it is pressing
ahead with its $10.7 billion unsolicited bid for Time Inc. although
Time has rejected Paramount's proposal and announced its own $14
billion tender offer for Warner Communications Inc.
   Most observers said the offer announced Friday complicated the
struggle for Time, which is trying to preserve the merger with
Warner announced in March.
   Time outlined a two-stage tender offer under which it would pay
$70 a share in cash for 100 million Warner shares in a tender offer
and then exchange $70 a share in cash and securities for the
remaining 100 million shares of Warner stock.
   Time stock slumped $9 to $162.50 a share in New York Stock
Exchange consolidated trading Friday, Warner rose $3.62{ to $59.25 a
share and Paramount fell $1.37{ to $58.12{.
   Analysts said there was still speculation on Wall Street that the
Paramount bid might succeed and that prevented Time stock from
falling further.
   Time's rejection of the Paramount $175-a-share bid _ which ended
10 days of silence on the offer _ said it was not in the best
interests of Time because the bid was financially inadequate and
highly conditional.
   Time officials said they anticipated a higher offer from
Paramount, but they believed Paramount still would ultimately fail
because its offer was conditioned on acquiring rights to some 800
cable system franchises that Time now holds.
   Time President Nicholas J. Nicholas said in an interview Friday
there has never been a hostile takeover of a cable franchise and he
predicted Paramount would be unable to operate the systems and
therefore would not have the assets needed to secure its takeover
debt.
   ``If you can't get hold of the assets, you can't get hold of the
bank loan,'' he said.
   Time officials also said they were betting stockholders would not
want to wait for Paramount to complete the regulatory process, which
Time estimated could take as long as a year.
   Some observers have cautioned that the bid for Warner could open
the company up to a higher bid by a third party. But Warner Chairman
Steven Ross discounted that possibility Friday.
   Paramount called Time's bid for Warner ``a defensive device, pure
and simple.''
   ``From the standpoint of Time shareholders, we don't see how it
begins to compare with our offer of $175 a share in cash for all
share,'' Paramount stated.
   Industry analysts have said the stock price of a combined
Time-Warner is unlikely to rise to the $175-a-share level for two
years. Nicholas vehemently disagreed, and said the combined cash
flow of a Time-Warner would be high enough to improve the stock's
value.
   A bid for Warner widely had been seen as a possible defensive
action by Time, but analysts said it did little to resolve the fight.
   Fred Anschel of Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. said the bid fails to
specify the exact breakdown of the cash and securities in the second
tier of the buyout and did not adequately explain how the deal would
be financed.
   However, Nicholas, Ross and Time Chairman J. Richard Munro said
in an interview that the Time-Warner cash flow would be enough to
service the debt resulting from the merger.
   Time and Warner also announced Friday they had carried out a
stock swap provided for under their earlier merger agreement. The
stock swap was intended to defend an unsolicited bid for either
company.
   Time also sued to block Paramount from taking any steps ``to
disrupt the merger'' of Time and Warner Communications Inc.
   The suit, filed at federal court in Manhattan, alleged Paramount
violated securities laws and sought a preliminary injunction to
prevent Paramount from trying to acquire Time stock and ``making or
attempting to make any tender offer'' for Time's securities.
   The lawsuit alleged that Paramount made false and misleading
statements in its tender offer.
   Paramount's statement called the suit ``a continuation of the
publicity campaign Time has been waging.''
   Paul Alexandrakis, an analyst with Argus Research Inc., said he
expected shareholders to determine the outcome of the fight _ either
by tendering their shares or in formal votes.
   However, Alexandrakis said, ``You might wonder why someone would
tender to Time rather than Paramount at this point with the
divergence in price.''
   Time and Warner agreed in March to merge in an all-stock deal
under which Time stockholders would get a share in the new company,
Time-Warner Inc., for each Time share while Warner shareholders
would get 0.465 of a share of the new company for each of their
Warner shares.
   Paramount, formerly called Gulf &amp; Western Inc., announced its bid
for Time on June 6, just 2{ weeks before Time and Warner
shareholders were to vote on the proposed merger. The tender offer
was formally launched the next day.
   Time and Warner did not immediately say whether their shareholder
meetings, scheduled for June 23, would take place.
</TEXT>
